# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: italy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] The **revolutions of 1848**, also known as the **springtime of the peoples**, were a series of revolutions throughout Europe that spanned almost two years, between January 1848 and October 1849.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] They remain the most widespread revolutionary wave in European history to date.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] The revolutions varied widely in their aims but generally opposed conservative systems, such as absolute monarchy and feudalism, and sought to establish nation states, founded on constitutionalism and popular sovereignty.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] The revolutionary wave began with the revolution in Sicily in January and spread across Europe after the revolution in France in February 1848.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Over fifty countries were affected, but with no significant coordination or cooperation among their respective revolutionaries.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Some of the major political contributing factors were widespread dissatisfaction with political leadership, demands for more participation in government and democracy, for freedom of the press, and by the working class for economic rights, and the rise of nationalism.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Other economic factors, such as the European potato failure, triggered mass starvation, migration, and civil unrest.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] The uprisings were led by temporary coalitions of workers and reformers, including figures from the middle and upper classes (the bourgeoisie); however, these coalitions did not hold together for long.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Many of the revolutions were quickly suppressed, as tens of thousands of people were killed, and even more were forced into exile.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Despite this, significant lasting reforms included the abolition of serfdom in Austria and Hungary, the end of absolute monarchy in Denmark, and the introduction of representative democracy in the Netherlands.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] The revolutions were most prominent in France, Italy, the Austrian Empire, and the states of the German Confederation that would make up the German Empire in the late 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] The wave of uprisings ended in October 1849.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] The revolutions were shaped by a wide variety of causes, which were linked to the short- and long-term socioeconomic transformations brought about by industrialization and the political legacy of the French Revolution.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] In addition to longer-term trends, an acute economic crisis between 1845 and 1847, resulting from the combination of a food crisis and an industrial recession, led to significant civil unrest and revolutionary agitation.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] The failure of governments to adequately address popular demands for reform led to an accumulation of discontent across Europe, culminating in the simultaneous outbreak of revolutions across the continent in 1848.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] According to Jonathan Sperber, conflict over agricultural land rights was the most prevalent form of social conflict in the pre-revolutionary period.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] The abolition of feudalism in parts of Western and Central Europe (especially in France) in the wake of the French Revolutionary and Napoleonic Wars had major ramifications for the rural populace.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Customary rights that peasants had once held on common land, especially to acquire wood from communal forests, were increasingly lost with the enclosure and privatization of the commons.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] These processes were often aided by modernizing states, such as France, which, with the enactment of the Forest Code of 1827, legally abolished peasants' rights to forests and the wood within them.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Peasants resorted to both legal and violent means to reclaim their land rights.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Lawsuits were frequently filed by peasants against landowners, and could remain active for decades; one such lawsuit in Sicily was first brought in 1829 and not settled until 1896.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Peasants also stole wood from privatized forests or occupied them to reassert their land rights by force.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Wood theft in particular was widespread in parts of Germany.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Between the 1820s and 1840s, the number of those convicted of wood theft in the Bavarian Palatinate increased from 37,500 in 1821–22 to 185,000 in 1846–47, accounting for a third of the population.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] In France, opposition to the Forest Code led to the "War of the Maidens" from 1829 to 1832, in which peasants disguised in women's clothes violently resisted the Code's implementation in the department of Ariège.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Unrest among the peasantry was also widespread in regions that retained feudalism, as in parts of Central Europe and most of Eastern Europe, though this had been commonplace for several centuries.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Disputes and revolts were directed variously at oppressive lords, taxation and military conscription by the state, and religious authorities.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] The largest pre-revolutionary peasant uprising against feudal lords occurred in Austrian Galicia in 1846, which put an end to the Kraków Uprising by the Polish nobility.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Rapid population growth was the most serious issue affecting urban workers, as migration into the cities due to poor conditions in the countryside led to a major oversaturation of labour markets and a decline in real wages among workers, while the cost of living continued to increase.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Poor workers became more vulnerable to economic shocks, and the inability to afford foodstuffs other than potatoes and bread proved catastrophic amid a major food crisis affecting both between 1845 and 1847.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Industrialization and the transition from the traditional economy to capitalist production also negatively affected urban workers, leading to a decline in their standard of living and social status.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Most workers in 1848 were artisans who worked in the trades, while there were relatively few factory workers.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Mechanization threatened some trades, such as the textile industry and metalworking, leading to a growing sense of insecurity among artisans, who felt their livelihoods and economic agency threatened.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] The most prevalent disputes, however, were between employers and workers.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Master craftsmen and journeymen came into increasing conflict as the guild system was weakened across Europe in the early nineteenth century.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Under the new economy, master craftsmen began to accumulate wealth and were able to hire more workers, many of whom were unemployed due to the massive surplus of artisans.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] At the same time, masters sought to prevent the growing number of journeymen and apprentices from ever advancing to become masters to protect their economic interests from growing competition.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Both master craftsmen and journeymen were threatened by economic transformations within the proto-industrial putting-out system, in which self-employed artisans were contracted by capitalist merchants to manufacture finished products.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Conflict between merchants and artisans, especially in the textile industry, was primarily over payment disputes, as merchants frequently underpaid outworkers for their finished products to maximize profit.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] These disputes led to civil unrest, including uprisings by weavers in Lyon in 1831 and 1834, and in Silesia in 1844.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Deep frustration among artisans continued into 1848, as they demanded the right of association to reclaim economic agency lost during the transition.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] This was advocated for both in novel forms such as the establishment of cooperatives, mutual benefit societies, and early trade unions, as in France, or through a return to the traditional guild system, as in Germany.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] The educated middle class was also affected by a decline in living standards.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Across Western Europe, industrialization had increased the demand for professionals to support the new industries.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Societal expectations also began to favor education and careerism as means to achieve upward mobility, especially after the French Revolution.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] As a result, more young men across Europe enrolled in universities, expecting, according to Lenore O'Boyle, that "the diploma might do what a title of nobility had once done" and they would achieve positions of leadership in society.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] In the more industrialized economies of Britain and the United States, more educated men were able to find work in private businesses, and consequently, there was little to no revolutionary agitation among them in 1848.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] In mainland Europe, however, where the pace of industrialization lagged, the only available professional careers were in the civil service, which could not open enough positions to meet demand.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] The lack of work led to dissatisfaction among the educated, who felt that they were unable to live as their status demanded.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] This issue was most pronounced in Germany, where overcrowding in professional careers was so severe that it gave rise to what sociologist Wilhelm Heinrich Riehl termed an "intellectual proletariat" of "underpaid and aspiring lower civil servants, journalists, and schoolteachers".
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] The intellectual proletariat was so numerous in Germany that, according to Riehl, they, not manual labourers, comprised "the real proletariat".
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Apart from the overcrowding of the professions, the middle class was also often deliberately excluded from political life and the bureaucracy by the state.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Positions in the bureaucracy were restricted to those who could afford the education required for them, and, especially in France and the Austrian Empire, aristocrats remained influential, hindering career advancement.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Professionals who could not find work turned to journalism as "the last refuge of those who had failed in other middle-class or professional careers", and were able to channel their frustration into political agitation, eventually becoming leaders in the revolutions in 1848.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] New political ideologies were emerging in the 1840s that would go on to influence the revolutions in 1848, with liberalism, radicalism, and nationalism being the principal opposition movements to European governments.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Liberals formed a distinct political force in the 19th century but varied widely in their beliefs.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Generally, liberals supported equality before the law and the protection of civil liberties, such as the freedoms of speech, the press, association, religion, and especially to own property, and favoured constitutions to achieve such.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] They opposed both absolute monarchies and radical republics, which they viewed as equally despotic, and favoured constitutional monarchies as a balance between the two extremes.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] They favoured popular sovereignty, but made a distinction between "the people" and "the rabble".
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] To that end, liberalism generally sought a restriction of the franchise to male property-owners.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Liberals were reluctant to engage in revolution or seek popular support due to their fears of a radical takeover and violent mob rule, as they had experienced during the French Revolution under the Jacobins and the Reign of Terror.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Liberals saw gradual, political reforms and economic development through parliaments, free markets, industrialization, and public education as means by which societal equality could be achieved, as more men could become property-owners and enter into political life.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] When liberals gained power, as in the July Monarchy in France after 1830, they trended toward conservatism, and their restriction of political life alienated wide swaths of the population, bringing them into conflict with the radical left.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Radicalism generally represented the loose and ill-defined coalition of democrats and socialists.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Radicals differed from moderate liberals in their support for democracy and universal manhood suffrage, extending the franchise to all adult men.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Both liberals and radicals shared in their opposition to "backwards" institutions, and especially in their anti-clericalism, which was considered synonymous with liberal and left-wing thought, though radicals were notably more violent in their opposition.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] While liberals were generally more concerned with political and legal questions and sought the expansion of civil liberties, radicals placed greater weight on the "social question", or the question of how to address the growth and precarity of the working poor in the capitalist economy.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Radicals were divided as to how to address the social question; radical democrats generally sought to address the social question through regulation and state intervention, whereas socialists sought the abolition of capitalism and economic redistribution.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Some radical democrats were economic liberals who tended to support political reform, especially universal manhood suffrage, over economic reform, and did not support government intervention of any sort.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Both democrats and socialists were, however, united in their desire to overthrow the existing regimes through revolution.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] "Nationalism" promoted the unity and primacy of people bound by some mix of common language, culture, religion, shared history and destiny, and immediate geography.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Political participation was increasing in the pre-revolutionary period, though it was limited in scope, and what forms existed were heavily restricted by state authorities.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Where elections were held, very few people could vote or run for office due to strict property requirements; in France, for example, the franchise was open to 0.5 percent of the population, or 241,000 people out of a population of 26 million.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Outside of elections, the reading, writing, and publishing of newspapers was the most basic form of political participation and expression, and the means by which political awareness as a whole was expanding.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Papers such as the *Rheinische Zeitung* in Germany and *La Réforme* in France became outlets for oppositional thought.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Circulation was generally low, ranging from several thousand for regional papers to hundreds for town and city papers.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] However, newspapers were often available to read communally or were read aloud to large public gatherings for those who were illiterate, allowing for a wider dissemination of political thought.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Mass politics was carried out through public celebrations, such as festivals and banquets, which were organized as *de facto* political rallies to circumvent state restrictions on them.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Informal political organizations existed to a degree in informal social circles, such as reading clubs, coffeehouses, and Masonic lodges.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Formal political parties and organizations were largely banned, leading the editorial staffs of newspapers to also became leaders of the political opposition.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] What formal organizations did exist were in the form of illegal secret societies, many of which attempted to organize unsuccessful uprisings in the pre-revolutionary period.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Among the most famous was the Young Italy movement, part of the larger Young Europe international network led by Giuseppe Mazzini, whose activism and methods in political organization were widely admired by contemporaries and imitated by other revolutionaries.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] According to economic historians Helge Berger and Mark Spoerer, the most immediate cause of the revolutions of 1848 was the multitudinous economic crisis between 1845 and 1847.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] The crisis began with a major food crisis in Europe in 1845.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] *Phytophthora infestans*, the microorganism responsible for potato blight, arrived in Europe from North America around 1840 and spread rapidly during a period of unusually wet weather in 1845, devastating harvests across Northern Europe.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Potatoes had become a staple food due to their high nutritional value and affordability, and were being grown on a large scale to feed growing populations, especially in Northern Europe.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] The effects of the potato blight were most severe in Ireland, where the Great Famine directly killed over an eighth of the population, or over 1 million people out of a population of 8 million.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Other countries, including Scotland, Belgium, and the Netherlands saw similar damage to crops, with 60,000 deaths in the Netherlands due to the potato blight.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Drought conditions in 1846 stopped the spread of the potato blight but damaged grain harvests, resulting in a sharp increase in food prices across the continent, and consequently virtually all foodstuffs became unaffordable for the poor.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Food riots erupted across Europe as the poor attempted by force to stave off starvation, with over 400 such riots in France between 1846 and 1847 and 164 riots in the German states in 1847.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Although severe famine was averted in most countries through strong government intervention, the rising cost of food, coupled with poor cotton harvests from the Southern United States necessary for textile manufacture, led to a major industrial recession in 1847.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Berger and Spoerer found a strong correlation among the countries that were most deeply affected by the industrial shock of 1847 and those that underwent a revolution in 1848.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] The revolutionary events in 1848 began after the "February Revolution" in France, which overthrew the July Monarchy and led to the establishment of the French Second Republic.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] The revolution in France was not the first to occur, as a revolution had already occurred in January in the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] In previous years, the Greater Poland uprising in 1846 and the Sonderbund War in Switzerland in 1847 had also seen similarly violent struggles for political reform.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] However, the revolution in France held far greater import among contemporaries due to the central role of France in European politics after the French Revolution, and the belief that the events in France were a portent for the rest of Europe.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Within weeks of the revolution in France, similar uprisings occurred in Munich, Vienna, Buda and Pest, Venice, Krakow, Milan, and Berlin through early-to-mid March.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] As the revolutions spread, reformers across Europe demanded the formation of a representative parliament, the freedom of the press, freedom of association, universal manhood suffrage, and the arming of the people under a national guard.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Faced with overwhelming political pressure, governments capitulated without offering significant resistance, and granted various political concessions.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] In Austria, after violent clashes in Vienna from 13 to 15 March, Metternich was forced to resign and went into exile, and Emperor Ferdinand I pledged to grant an imperial constitution.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Revolution broke out in Hungary shortly afterward, and the Diet of Hungary successfully appealed for Hungarian national sovereignty within the Habsburg monarchy.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] When the news from Vienna reached Austrian-ruled northern Italy some days later, revolutionary governments were declared in Milan and Venice, and the Kingdom of Piedmont–Sardinia declared war on Austria, beginning the First Italian War of Independence.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] In Prussia, after a brief but deadly spate of barricade fighting in Berlin on 18 March, King Frederick William IV ordered the army to withdraw, appointed a liberal ministry, and committed Prussia to the cause of German national unification.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] The earliest months of the revolutions were characterized by profound political change across Europe.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Elections were held under broad franchises through the spring of 1848 for newly established or reformed parliaments.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Political participation increased substantially among the people as press censorship was relaxed and restrictions on association were lifted under the new constitutions.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Political clubs and newspapers massively increased in number, extending political awareness to far more people than in the pre-revolutionary period.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] A labour movement also began to develop during the early revolutions, though workers' associations were less organized and widespread compared to political clubs.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] A "revolutionary psychosis" was felt across Europe during the earliest phase of the revolutions as people celebrated the accomplishments of the "springtime of the peoples".
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Even in the smallest provincial towns in Germany "there were illuminations, festive parades by the riflemen’s associations, banquets of local notables, and embracing in the streets".
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] The early revolutions, however, also saw widespread violence and a major increase in social conflict, as people of all backgrounds sought to affect a social revolution and further their position or to violently seek revenge for various grievances.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] In urban centres, rioters ransacked the homes and offices of their employers, broke machines and destroyed factories and workshops, and attacked tax collectors and customs officials.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] National conflicts also began to emerge in the late spring of 1848, especially in Germany and the multi-ethnic Austrian Empire.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Efforts toward German national unification led to conflict with other nationalities within German territory, including Poles, Danes, and Czechs.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] In the Grand Duchy of Posen in eastern Prussia, an uprising by Polish nationalists led to conflict between Germans and Poles, despite earlier German support for Polish independence; the uprising was suppressed by Prussian troops by April.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] In Schleswig, the German population revolted against efforts by Denmark to annex the duchy, and were supported by the German states, leading to the First Schleswig War.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Some maximalist German nationalists also sought to extend the German nation to the crown lands of the Habsburg monarchy, including the German Archduchy of Austria as well as Czech Bohemia, Slovenian Carniola, and Italian Trieste and Trentino.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] National conflicts pervaded throughout the entire Habsburg monarchy, especially in Hungary, where non-Magyars (especially Croats and Romanians) resisted attempts to form a homogeneous Hungarian nation, as well as in Galicia between Poles and Ruthenians, and Bohemia between Czechs and Germans.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] In the summer of 1848, serious divisions emerged in France between radical workers and the moderate government.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] In the early spring, the provisional government had been able to rely on their support, agreeing to their demands for the right to work and the "organization of labour" through the formation of the national workshops.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] However, after the conservative victory in the Constituent Assembly elections on 23 April and the radical attempt to overthrow the Assembly on 15 May, the new French government came under pressure to close them.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] After 15 May, the government also began to repress the left by jailing its leaders, closing its clubs and newspapers, and dissolving the Luxembourg Commission.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] On 21 June, the national workshops were closed, leading to a major insurrection by workers against the government, known as the "June Days".
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] The uprising was suppressed with significant bloodshed by General Louis-Eugène Cavaignac, who was vested with dictatorial powers by the Constituent Assembly to restore order, targeting both the insurgents and the left-wing opposition in general.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] The counter-revolution in the Austrian Empire was carried out largely by the army and conservatives in the Habsburg court.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] The first Habsburg victories were against the June Uprising in Prague, provoked by the reactionary Alfred I, Prince of Windisch-Grätz.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] The uprising was suppressed when the city was bombarded with artillery, despite attempts at conciliation by the liberal government of Baron Franz von Pillersdorf.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] More crucially in northern Italy, the army under Joseph Radetzky defeated the disorganized Piedmontese army at the Battle of Custoza in July, leaving Austria in near-total control of its Italian provinces.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] As conservatives gained strength, they mobilized Josip Jelačić, the Ban of Croatia, to invade Hungary and put an end to its sovereignty.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] The beginning of the Hungarian War of Independence on 11 September led to the Vienna Uprising in October, during which radicals occupied the city for three weeks, until they were crushed by the forces of Jelačić and Windisch-Grätz on 31 October.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] In Germany, the counter-revolution began in the early autumn of 1848 with the reaction to the Armistice of Malmö, signed between Prussia and Denmark to temporarily suspend the Schleswig War.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Although Prussia's unilateral action undermined the Frankfurt parliament's supremacy, the parliament was forced to accept the armistice due to the threat of a war with the great powers, especially Russia.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Widespread anger at the Frankfurt parliament's "betrayal" of the German revolution, combined with frustration among the lower classes at the slow pace of reform, led to the outbreak of renewed uprisings in western Germany in September.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] The radical uprisings were crushed by the German states, with the support of the central government established by the Frankfurt parliament.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] With the execution of parliamentary deputy Robert Blum by Austrian troops at the end of the October uprising, the Frankfurt parliament's claims of exercising authority over any part of Germany were further discredited.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] By the end of 1848, the springtime of the peoples was effectively over, and decidedly conservative governments had come into power across Europe.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] In Prussia, Frederick William IV, with the support of the army, carried out a *coup d'état*, dismissing the liberal ministers he appointed in the spring and imposing a conservative constitution.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] In Austria, Emperor Ferdinand I was made to abdicate in favour of his nephew Franz Joseph I, under the expectation that he would not be beholden to the constitutionalist concessions made during the revolutions.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] In France, Louis Napoléon Bonaparte, nephew of the last French emperor, was elected president, in large part with the backing of conservatives, who expected him to restore public order in the wake of the June Days.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] At the end of 1848, the revolutions were over where they had begun, with the major centres in Paris, Vienna, Berlin, and Milan largely pacified.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] However, the expansion of political activity in 1848 allowed for radicals to begin organizing in new regions outside of the major cities.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] In France and Germany, left-wing organizations turned to the provinces, achieving greater support among rural workers in parliamentary elections in 1849.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Meanwhile, in central Italy and Hungary, the revolutions gained new strength, and established new regimes to contest the old order.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] In central Italy, radicals gained power in the Grand Duchy of Tuscany and the Papal States, proclaiming the Tuscan Republic and the Roman Republic in February.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Together with Piedmont–Sardinia, where radicals won the parliamentary elections, the new revolutionary governments in Italy began to make plans for an all-Italian constituent assembly, as had been formed in Germany, and resumed the war with Austria.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Piedmont–Sardinia was again decisively defeated by Austria at the Battle of Novara in March, resulting in the abdication of Piedmontese King Charles Albert and the end of the war in August.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Counter-revolution continued in the Habsburg empire under the new emperor Franz Joseph, with the imperial government dissolving the Reichstag and rejecting its constitutional proposal in favour of the imposed March Constitution.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] The new constitution applied to the entire empire, ending Hungary's autonomy and mandating its partition into several military districts.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] In response, Hungary declared full independence from the Habsburg empire and dethroned Franz Joseph as King of Hungary.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Through the spring, Hungary launched a military campaign that led to the recapture of almost all of Hungary's territory from Habsburg forces.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Facing a new crisis in Hungary, the Habsburg empire appealed for Russia's intervention in "the holy struggle against anarchy".
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] Russia mobilized 200,000 troops to invade Hungary, combined with 175,000 Habsburg troops, against the 170,000 troops of Hungary, many of whom were ill-equipped and exhausted.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] For Russia's support, Austria offered no concessions, and Russia demanded none.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] In Germany, after much deliberation, the Frankfurt National Assembly agreed to the Frankfurt Constitution for the new German Empire in March 1849, and elected Frederick William IV to serve as Emperor of the Germans.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] However, he rejected the crown on the basis that the Assembly did not have the authority to confer it, and he further denounced the Frankfurt Constitution, refusing any restrictions on his monarchical powers.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] In response, a new wave of uprisings swept through Germany during the Imperial Constitution campaign as radicals, working largely among the lower classes, sought to force the acceptance of the Frankfurt Constitution.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] The campaign, lasting between May and July 1849, ultimately ended in defeat, ending the German revolutions.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] After the summer of 1849, the last remaining revolutionary regimes were in Rome, Venice, and Hungary.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] The revolutionary Roman Republic was defeated in July after the intervention of France, and Venice surrendered in August after enduring more than a year of siege and isolation.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] With the entry of Russia into the war, Hungary, the last revolutionary state, was placed on the defensive, suffering numerous defeats between late June and August.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p01] On 13 August, Hungary surrendered to Austria and Russia, formally ending the war of independence; the last Hungarian holdouts at the fortress of Komárom surrendered between 2 and 5 October, marking the end of the revolutions of 1848.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The first of the numerous revolutions to occur in 1848 in Italy came in Palermo, Sicily, starting in January 1848.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] There had been several previous revolts against Bourbon rule; this one produced an independent state that lasted only 16 months before the Bourbons were restored to the throne.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] During those months, the constitution was quite advanced for its time in liberal democratic terms, as was the proposal of a unified Italian confederation of states.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The revolt's failure was reversed 12 years later as the Bourbon Kingdom of the Two Sicilies collapsed in 1860–61 with the unification of Italy.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] On 11 February 1848, Leopold II of Tuscany, first cousin of Emperor Ferdinand I of Austria, granted the Constitution, with the general approval of his subjects.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The Habsburg example was followed by Charles Albert of Sardinia (Albertine Statute; later became the constitution of the unified Kingdom of Italy and remained in force, with changes, until 1948) and by Pope Pius IX (Fundamental Statute).
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] However, only King Charles Albert maintained the statute even after the end of the riots.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Revolts broke out throughout the Kingdom of Lombardy–Venetia, such as the Five Days of Milan, which marked the beginning of the First Italian War of Independence.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] After declaring independence from the Habsburg Austrian Empire, the Republic of San Marco later joined the Kingdom of Sardinia in an attempt, led by the latter, to unite northern Italy against foreign (mainly Austrian but also French) domination.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] However, the First Italian War of Independence ended in the defeat of Sardinia, and Austrian forces reconquered the Republic of San Marco on 28 August 1849 following a long siege.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Based on the Venetian Lagoon, the Republic of San Marco extended into most of Venetia, or the *Terraferma* territory of the Republic of Venice, suppressed 51 years earlier in the French Revolutionary Wars.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] In the Duchy of Modena and Reggio, Duke Francis V attempted to respond militarily to the first attempts at armed revolt, but faced with the approach of Bolognese volunteers to support the insurgents, to avoid bloodshed, he preferred to leave the city, promising a constitution and amnesties.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] A provisional government was established in Modena.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] In the Papal States, an internal revolt ousted Pope Pius IX from his temporal powers and led to the establishment of the Roman Republic.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The municipalities of Menton and Roquebrune united and obtained independence from the Principality of Monaco, becoming a protectorate of the Kingdom of Sardinia, and would eventually join Sardinia in 1861.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The revolution against the July Monarchy in France began after the banning of the *campagne des banquets*, held to advocate for an expansion of the electoral franchise and to protest the conservative government of François Guizot.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Protests began on 22 February in Paris, led largely by workers and students, and quickly escalated into a revolution, especially after the army's massacre of 65 demonstrators on 23 February.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The revolution culminated on 24 February, when King Louis Philippe I abdicated and fled the country.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] With the fall of the July Monarchy, a provisional government was formed, consisting of a coalition of moderate republicans and socialists, and the French Second Republic was proclaimed.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Shortly after taking power, the provisional government instituted universal manhood suffrage and abolished slavery and the death penalty.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] To placate labour unrest, it recognized the right to work and established the publicly-run national workshops (*ateliers nationaux*) for the unemployed.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Louis Blanc, a socialist member of the provisional government, was appointed to lead the Luxembourg Commission, consisting of workers' delegates, to investigate economic reforms to address the social question.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Some actions proved unpopular in the provinces, such as the "commissioners of the republic" appointed as part of the regime change, whose conduct was criticized as dictatorial, and the 45 percent increase in the property tax to pay for the government's growing expenses.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The Constituent Assembly elections on 23 April returned a conservative majority, and the provisional government was replaced by the more moderate Executive Commission, which largely excluded socialists.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] After the demonstration of 15 May, the Executive Commission, under pressure from the Assembly, moved to close the national workshops.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Conservatives criticized the workshops as an unproductive waste of public funds, and viewed the growing number of workers in Paris as a source of revolt.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] With the closure of the workshops, workers would be conscripted into the army or sent home if they refused.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Facing possible destitution, workers launched the June Days uprising between 22 and 26 June, involving 40,000 to 50,000 insurgents in violent barricade fighting across Paris.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The uprising was suppressed by General Louis-Eugène Cavaignac, who was made France's head of state after the Executive Commission resigned on 24 June.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The first French presidential elections were held on 10 December after the adoption of the French Constitution of 1848 on 14 November.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The two leading candidates were Cavaignac and Louis Napoléon Bonaparte, the nephew of Napoleon, who returned from exile in England after winning in by-elections to the Constituent Assembly in September.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] In the presidential election, Bonaparte won in a landslide victory with 75 percent of the vote.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The revolution in France finally ended in December 1851, when Bonaparte launched a coup d'état to remain in office, as he was limited to a single term and failed to gain support for a constitutional amendment allowing him to run again.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The coup met little resistance except in the provinces, where the left-wing "Republican Solidarity" organization, with 100,000 members, led a failed uprising.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The following year, Bonaparte crowned himself as emperor of the Second French Empire, taking the name Napoleon III.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The success of the revolution in France provided the impetus for the German revolutions.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The first revolutionary events were in southwestern Germany, with popular demonstrations in Baden beginning on 27 February, followed by the rest of the small- to medium-sized German states.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Across Germany, the ubiquitous "March demands" (*Märzforderungen*) were issued, which called for, among other things, the immediate formation of a German national parliament.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Weeks later, the revolution spread to the Austrian capital of Vienna from 13 to 15 March and the Prussian capital of Berlin from 18 to 19 March, and was successful in both.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] At the initiative of middle-class reformers, the German states agreed to hold elections under universal manhood suffrage for a national parliament.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The Frankfurt National Assembly sat for the first time on 18 May, with the task of drafting a German constitution.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] It appointed the "Provisional Central Power" to act as a national government, with Archduke John of Austria as Imperial Regent.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] As the Assembly and the Central Power had no means of enforcing its authority, it relied on the cooperation of the German states, particularly Austria and Prussia, and their tenuous recognition of the Assembly's legitimacy.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Division and sometimes violent conflict between liberals and radicals over numerous issues characterized the German revolutions from their onset.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] One immediate point of contention was whether Germany should be a republic or a constitutional monarchy; the "pre-parliament" had voted to support the latter, leading to the Hecker uprising in Baden by the radical republicans Friedrich Hecker and Gustav Struve in April 1848.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The reliance of the liberal Frankfurt National Assembly and Central Power on the states to suppress radical uprisings, such as in April, worsened divisions and demonstrated the weakness of the national government.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Another major point of contention was the "national question" of German unification.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] This included whether the German nation should include Austria (the "German question"), and whether it should include non-German lands.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Conflicts between Germans and other nationalities occurred in Bohemia against Czechs, Posen (now Poznań) against Poles (in the Greater Poland uprising), and Schleswig–Holstein against Danes (in the First Schleswig War).
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] In March 1849, despite divisions between liberals and radicals, the Frankfurt National Assembly concluded its work, presenting the Frankfurt Constitution for the German Empire.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Under the new constitution, the empire would be governed as a federal constitutional monarchy with significant democratic concessions, including universal manhood suffrage and the protection of minority rights, and ruled by the King of Prussia as hereditary Emperor of the Germans.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Austria, emboldened by the success of its counter-revolution, was excluded due to its insistence that all Habsburg territory and its multitude of non-German peoples be incorporated into the empire, threatening to upend the German nation-state.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Frederick William IV of Prussia ultimately rejected the crown, as he did not recognize the authority of the Frankfurt National Assembly, and also rejected the constitution, believing, under the divine right of kings, that his rule could not be restricted by one.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The rejection of the imperial crown led to the Imperial Constitution campaign, the final act of the German revolutions.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Uprisings again broke out across Germany in May 1849 in an effort to force the implementation of the constitution on the German states.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The uprisings had wide support among radicalized workers, bourgeoisie, and soldiers, who were coordinated by highly-developed political organizations.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Compared to the regular armies they faced, however, the revolutionaries were poorly armed and organized, and were quickly defeated in combat.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The uprising in Baden endured the longest, owing to significant support among the troops.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] It finally capitulated on 23 July 1849, marking the end of the revolutions in Germany.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Denmark had been governed by a system of absolute monarchy (King's Law) since the 17th century.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] King Christian VIII, a moderate reformer but still an absolutist, died in January 1848 during a period of rising opposition from farmers and liberals.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The demands for a constitutional monarchy, led by the National Liberals, ended with a popular march to Christiansborg on 21 March.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The new king, Frederick VII, met the liberals' demands and installed a new Cabinet that included prominent leaders of the National Liberal Party.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The national-liberal movement wanted to abolish absolutism, but retain a strongly centralized state.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The king accepted a new constitution, agreeing to share power with a bicameral parliament called the Rigsdag.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] It is said that the Danish king's first words after signing away his absolute power were, "that was nice, now I can sleep in the mornings".
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Although army officers were dissatisfied, they accepted the new arrangement.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] In contrast to the rest of Europe, this was not overturned by reactionaries.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The liberal constitution did not extend to Schleswig, leaving the Schleswig-Holstein Question unanswered.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The Duchy of Schleswig, a region containing both Danes (a North Germanic population) and Germans (a West Germanic population), was a part of the Danish monarchy, but remained a duchy separate from the Kingdom of Denmark.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Spurred by pan-Germanist sentiment, the Germans of Schleswig took up arms against a proposal from the National Liberal government in Copenhagen, which would have fully integrated the duchy into Denmark.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The German population in Schleswig and Holstein revolted, inspired by the Protestant clergy.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The German states sent in an army, but Danish victories in 1849 led to the Treaty of Berlin (1850) and the London Protocol (1852).
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] They reaffirmed the sovereignty of the King of Denmark, while prohibiting union with Denmark.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The violation of the latter provision led to renewed warfare in 1863 and the Prussian victory in 1864.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] From March 1848 through July 1849, the Habsburg Austrian Empire was threatened by revolutionary movements, which often had a nationalist character.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The nationalist picture was further complicated by the simultaneous events in the German states, which moved toward greater German national unity.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] On 15 April, Emperor Ferdinand I declared himself a "constitutional monarch", despite there not yet being a constitution.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] He charged Baron Franz von Pillersdorf with drafting one, and it was passed on 25 April 1848.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] This constitution, called the Pillersdorf Constitution, applied to the whole of the Habsburg monarchy, except for Hungary.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The constitution established the Reichstag, a short-lived unicameral parliamentary body.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The Reichstag had two goals: to reform the feudal system and to draft a new constitution.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] It succeeded in its first goal, abolishing serfdom by a patent issued together with the Emperor on 7 September 1848.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] In the midst of its work, the Reichstag was relocated to Kroměříž (German: *Kremsier*) in Moravia due to the Vienna Uprising in October 1848.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The Reichstag was due to present its liberal constitution, the Kremsier Constitution, on the anniversary of the revolution in 1849, but the abdication of Ferdinand I in favor of his more conservative nephew Franz Joseph I in December 1848 prevented such.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] As the revolutions came to an end in Europe, the Austrian army dissolved the Reichstag on 7 March 1849, and the imperial government promulgated the March Constitution, which strengthened the powers of the emperor.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The Hungarian Revolution of 1848 was the longest in Europe, crushed in August 1849 by the Austrian and Russian armies.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Nevertheless, it had a major effect in freeing the serfs.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] It began on 15 March 1848, when Hungarian patriots organized mass demonstrations in Pest and Buda (today Budapest) which forced the imperial governor to accept their 12 points of demands.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] On that morning, the demands were read aloud along with poetry by Sándor Petőfi with the simple lines of "We swear by the God of the Hungarians; we swear, we shall be slaves no more".
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Lajos Kossuth and other liberal nobles in the Hungarian Diet appealed to the Habsburg court with demands for representative government and civil liberties.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] These events resulted in Klemens von Metternich, the Austrian chancellor and foreign minister, resigning.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The demands of the Diet were agreed upon on 18 March by Emperor Ferdinand I.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Although Hungary would remain part of the monarchy through personal union with the emperor, a constitutional government would be founded.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The Diet then passed the April laws that established equality before the law, a legislature, a hereditary constitutional monarchy, and an end to the transfer and restrictions of land use.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The revolution grew into a war for independence from the Habsburg monarchy when Josip Jelačić, Ban of Croatia, crossed the border to restore their control.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The new government, led by Lajos Kossuth, was initially successful against the Habsburg forces.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Although Hungary took a national united stand for its freedom, some minorities of the Kingdom of Hungary, including the Serbs of Vojvodina, the Romanians of Transylvania, and some Slovaks of Upper Hungary, supported the Habsburg Emperor and fought against the Hungarian Revolutionary Army.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Eventually, after one and a half years of fighting, the revolution was crushed when Russian Tsar Nicholas I marched into Hungary with over 300,000 troops.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] As a result of the defeat, Hungary was thus placed under brutal martial law.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The leading rebels like Kossuth went into exile or were executed, the latter including former prime minister Batthyány and the Thirteen Martyrs of Arad.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] In the long run, the passive resistance following the revolution, along with the crushing Austrian defeat in the 1866 Austro-Prussian War, led to the Austro-Hungarian Compromise (1867), which marked the start of the Austro-Hungarian Empire.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The center of the Ukrainian national movement was in Galicia, which is today divided between Ukraine and Poland.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] On 19 April 1848, a group of representatives led by the Greek Catholic clergy launched a petition to the Austrian Emperor.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] On 2 May 1848, the Supreme Ruthenian Council was established.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The council (1848–1851) was headed by the Greek-Catholic Bishop Gregory Yakhimovich and consisted of 30 permanent members.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Its main goal was the administrative division of Galicia into Western (Polish) and Eastern (Ruthenian/Ukrainian) parts within the borders of the Habsburg Empire, and formation of a separate region with a political self-governance.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Though both Polish and Ruthenian Galicians had nationalist aspirations, the two groups' interests diverged, with Polish nobles in Ruthenia often having dominion over Ruthenian serfs.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Emperor Ferdinand responded to Galician agitation in 1848 by freeing the predominantly Ruthenian serfs, thereby dampening the revolutionary ardor of both groups.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The revolution of 1848 in Bohemia began with the drafting of a list of liberal demands of the Czech population of the Czech lands at the St.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Wenceslas Spa in Prague by the wealthier inhabitants of the city in March.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] These were spurred by the more violent events in Vienna and the news of revolutions sweeping across the continent.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Austroslavism emerged during the revolutions, propagated by František Palacký, which sought to achieve greater autonomy for the Czech lands, and potentially even a federation, within the Habsburg monarchy, as opposed to potentially all of the Czech lands joining a unified greater Germany.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Switzerland, already an alliance of republics, also saw an internal struggle.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The attempted secession of seven Catholic cantons to form an alliance known as the *Sonderbund* ("separate alliance", "special alliance") in 1845 led to a short civil conflict in November 1847 in which around 100 people were killed.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The *Sonderbund* was decisively defeated by the Protestant cantons, which had a larger population.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] A new constitution of 1848 ended the almost-complete independence of the cantons, transforming Switzerland into a federal state.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Polish people mounted a military insurrection against the Prussians in the Grand Duchy of Posen (or the Greater Poland region), a part of Prussia since its annexation in 1815.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The Poles tried to establish a Polish political entity, but refused to cooperate with the Germans and the Jews.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The Germans decided they were better off with the status quo, so they assisted the Prussian governments in recapturing control.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] In the long-term, the uprising stimulated nationalism among both the Poles and the Germans and brought civil equality to the Jews.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] A Romanian liberal and Romantic nationalist uprising began in June in the principality of Wallachia.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Its goals were administrative autonomy, abolition of serfdom, and popular self-determination.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] It was closely connected with the 1848 unsuccessful revolt in Moldavia, it sought to overturn the administration imposed by Imperial Russian authorities under the *Regulamentul Organic* regime, and, through many of its leaders, demanded the abolition of boyar privilege.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Despite its rapid gains and popular backing, the new administration was marked by conflicts between the radical wing and more conservative forces, especially over the issue of land reform.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Two successive abortive coups weakened the new government, and its international status was always contested by Russia.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] After managing to rally a degree of sympathy from Ottoman political leaders, the Revolution was ultimately isolated by the intervention of Russian diplomats.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] In September 1848, by agreement with the Ottomans, Russia invaded and put down the revolution.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] In later decades, the rebels returned and gained their goals.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Belgium did not see major unrest in 1848; it had already undergone a liberal reform after the Revolution of 1830, and thus its constitutional system and its monarchy survived.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Many small local riots broke out, concentrated in the *sillon industriel* industrial region of the provinces of Liège and Hainaut.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The most serious threat of revolutionary contagion, however, was posed by Belgian émigré groups from France.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] In 1830, the Belgian Revolution had broken out, inspired by the revolution occurring in France, and Belgian authorities feared that a similar 'copycat' phenomenon might occur in 1848.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Shortly after the revolution in France, Belgian migrant workers living in Paris were encouraged to return to Belgium to overthrow the monarchy and establish a republic.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Belgian authorities expelled Karl Marx himself from Brussels in early March on accusations of having used part of his inheritance to arm Belgian revolutionaries.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Around 6,000 armed émigrés of the "Belgian Legion" attempted to cross the Belgian frontier.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] There were two divisions that were formed.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The first group, travelling by train, was stopped and quickly disarmed at Quiévrain on 26 March 1848.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The second group crossed the border on 29 March and headed for Brussels.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] They were confronted by Belgian troops at the hamlet of Risquons-Tout and defeated.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Several smaller groups managed to infiltrate Belgium, but the reinforced Belgian border troops succeeded, and the defeat at Risquons-Tout effectively ended the revolutionary threat to Belgium.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The situation in Belgium began to recover that summer after a good harvest, and fresh elections returned a strong majority to the governing party.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Previously a separate kingdom, Ireland was united with Great Britain to form the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland on 1 January 1801.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Although the Irish population was made up largely of rural Catholic agricultural workers, tensions arose from the political over-representation, in positions of power, of the Anglo-Irish, Protestant Ascendancy who were loyal to the union.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] From the 1810s onward, an Irish conservative-liberal movement led by Daniel O'Connell had sought to secure equal political rights for Catholics within the British political system, succeeding with the Roman Catholic Relief Act 1829.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] But as in other European states, a current inspired by Radicalism criticized Irish conservative-liberals for pursuing the aim of democratic equality with excessive compromise and gradualism.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] In Ireland, a current of nationalist, egalitarian and radicalist republicanism, inspired by the French Revolution, had been present since the 1790s – being expressed initially in the Irish Rebellion of 1798.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] This tendency grew into a movement for social, cultural, and political reform during the 1830s, and in 1839 was realized into a political association called Young Ireland.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] It was initially not well received, but grew more popular with the Great Famine of 1845–1849, an event that brought catastrophic social effects and which threw into light the inadequate response of authorities.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The act also limited who could own guns and, under penalty, coerced all Irish men between the ages of 16 and 60 to join in a type of posse comitatus in each district to assist in apprehending suspected murderers when killings took place, or else be guilty of a misdemeanour themselves.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] In response, the Young Ireland Party launched a rebellion in July 1848, gathering landlords and tenants to its cause.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] But its first major engagement against police, in the village of Ballingarry, South Tipperary, was a failure.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] A long gunfight with around 50 policemen ended when police reinforcements arrived.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] After the arrest of the Young Ireland leaders, the rebellion collapsed, though intermittent fighting continued for the next year.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] It is sometimes called the *Famine Rebellion* (since it took place during the Great Famine).
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The United Kingdom, Belgium, the Netherlands, Portugal, the Russian Empire (including Poland and Finland), and the Ottoman Empire did not encounter major national or Radical revolutions in 1848.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Sweden and Norway were also little affected.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Serbia, though formally unaffected by the revolt as it was a part of the Ottoman state, actively supported Serbian revolutionaries in the Habsburg Empire.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] In many countries, the absence of unrest was partly due to governments taking action to prevent revolutionary unrest and pre-emptively granting some of the reforms demanded by revolutionaries elsewhere.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] This was notably the case for the Netherlands, where King William II decided to alter the Dutch constitution to reform elections and voluntarily reduce the power of the monarchy.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The same might be said of Switzerland, where a new constitutional regime was introduced in 1848: the Swiss Federal Constitution was a revolution of sorts, laying the foundation of Swiss society as it is today.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] In the United Kingdom, while the middle classes had been pacified by their inclusion in the extension of the franchise in the Reform Act 1832, the consequential agitations, violence, and petitions of the Chartist movement came to a head with their peaceful petition to Parliament of 1848.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The repeal in 1846 of the protectionist agricultural tariffs – called the "Corn Laws" – had defused some proletarian fervour.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] In the Isle of Man, there were ongoing efforts to reform the self-elected House of Keys, but no revolution took place.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Some of the reformers were encouraged by events in France in particular.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] In the United States, opinions were polarized, with Democrats and reformers in favour, although they were distressed at the degree of violence involved.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Opposition came from conservative elements, especially Whigs, southern slaveholders, orthodox Calvinists, and Catholics.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] About 4,000 German exiles arrived, and some became fervent Republicans in the 1850s, such as Carl Schurz.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Kossuth toured America and won great applause, but no volunteers or diplomatic or financial help.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Following rebellions in 1837 and 1838, 1848 in Canada saw the establishment of responsible government in Nova Scotia and The Canadas, the first such governments in the British Empire outside the United Kingdom.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Tory and Orange Order in Canada opposition to responsible government came to a head in riots triggered by the Rebellion Losses Bill in 1849.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] They succeeded in the burning of the Parliament Buildings in Montreal, but, unlike their counterrevolutionary counterparts in Europe, they were ultimately unsuccessful.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] In Spanish Latin America, the Revolution of 1848 appeared in New Granada, where Colombian students, liberals, and intellectuals demanded the election of General José Hilario López.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] He took power in 1849 and launched major reforms, abolishing slavery and the death penalty, and providing freedom of the press and of religion.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The resulting turmoil in Colombia lasted three decades; from 1851 to 1885, the country was ravaged by four general civil wars and 50 local revolutions.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] In Chile, the 1848 revolutions inspired the 1851 Chilean revolution.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] In Brazil, the Praieira Revolt, a movement in Pernambuco, lasted from November 1848 to 1852.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Unresolved conflicts from the period of the regency and local resistance to the consolidation of the Empire of Brazil that had been proclaimed in 1822 helped to plant the seeds of the revolution.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] In Mexico, the Centralist Republic led by Antonio López de Santa Anna lost half of its territory to the United States, including California and Texas, in the Mexican–American War of 1845–1848.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Derived from this catastrophe and chronic stability problems, the Liberal Party started a reformist movement.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] This movement, via elections, led liberals to formulate the *Plan of Ayutla*.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The Plan written in 1854 aimed at removing President Santa Anna from control of Mexico during the Second Federal Republic of Mexico period.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Initially, it seemed little different from other political plans of the era, but it is considered the first act of the Liberal Reform in Mexico.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] It was the catalyst for revolts in many parts of Mexico, which led to the resignation of Santa Anna from the presidency, never to vie for office again.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The next Presidents of Mexico were the liberals, Juan Álvarez, Ignacio Comonfort, and Benito Juárez.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The new regime would then proclaim the 1857 Mexican Constitution, which implemented a variety of liberal reforms.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Among other things, these reforms confiscated religious property, aimed to promote economic development, and to stabilize a nascent republican government.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The reforms led directly to the so-called Three Years War or Reform War of 1857.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The liberals won this war, but the conservatives solicited the French Government of Napoleon III for a European, conservative Monarch, deriving into the Second French intervention in Mexico.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Under the puppet Habsburg government of Maximilian I of Mexico, the country became a client state of France (1863–1867).
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] In the Dutch East Indies, a group of up to six hundred Indo people occupied the Harmonie Club in Batavia in May 1848 to protest against their exclusion from upper-rank colonial posts.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Administrators feared the liberal demonstration would spread to the region's Javanese or Chinese and even grow into an independence movement, and the organizers behind the protest were fired and banned from Java entirely.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Liberal democrats looked to 1848 as a democratic revolution, which in the long run ensured liberty, equality, and fraternity.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] For nationalists, 1848 was the springtime of hope, when newly emerging nationalities rejected the old multinational empires, but the results were not as comprehensive as many had hoped.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Communists denounced 1848 as a betrayal of working-class ideals by a bourgeoisie indifferent to the legitimate demands of the proletariat.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The view of the revolutions of 1848 as a bourgeois revolution is also common in non-Marxist scholarship.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Tensions over differing approaches between bourgeois revolutionaries and radicals played a major role in the failure of the revolutions.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Many governments engaged in a partial reversal of the revolutionary reforms of 1848–1849 as well as heightened repression and censorship.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The Hanoverian nobility successfully appealed to the Confederal Diet in 1851 over the loss of their noble privileges, while the Prussian Junkers recovered their manorial police powers from 1852 to 1855.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] In the Austrian Empire, the Sylvester Patents (1851) discarded Franz Stadion's constitution and the Statute of Basic Rights, while the number of arrests in Habsburg territories increased from 70,000 in 1850 to one million by 1854.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Nicholas I's rule in Russia after 1848 was particularly repressive, marked by an expansion of the secret police (the Tretiye Otdeleniye) and stricter censorship; more Russians were working for censorship organs than actual books published in the period immediately after 1848.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] In France, the works of Charles Baudelaire, Victor Hugo, Alexandre Ledru-Rollin, and Pierre-Joseph Proudhon were confiscated.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] In the post-revolutionary decade after 1848, little had visibly changed, and many historians considered the revolutions a failure, given the seeming lack of permanent structural changes.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] More recently, Christopher Clark has characterized the period that followed 1848 as one dominated by a revolution in government.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The conservative Prussian prime minister Otto von Manteuffel declared that the state could no longer be run like the landed estate of a nobleman.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Meanwhile, centrist coalitions, consisting of liberals and conservatives united in their anxiety toward working-class socialism, also took power after the revolutions, such as the *Connubio* coalition led by Camillo Benso, Count of Cavour in Piedmont–Sardinia.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Priscilla Robertson considered many of the revolutionaries' goals to have been achieved by the 1870s, though largely by the enemies of the revolutions.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Austria and Prussia eliminated feudalism by 1850 and Russia abolished serfdom in 1861, improving conditions for the peasants.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The European middle classes made political and economic gains over the next 20 years, with France retaining the universal male suffrage that had been established by the Second Republic.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The Austrian Empire was reorganized into the Dual Monarchy, according Hungary more self-determination as part of the *Ausgleich* of 1867, a process that was spearheaded by the former revolutionaries Gyula Andrássy and Ferenc Deák.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Karl Marx expressed disappointment at the bourgeois character of the revolutions.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Marx elaborated in his 1850 "Address of the Central Committee to the Communist League" a theory of permanent revolution according to which the proletariat should strengthen democratic bourgeois revolutionary forces until the proletariat itself is ready to seize power.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] German historian Reinhard Rürup described the 1848 revolutions as a turning point in the development of modern antisemitism.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] About 4,000 exiles went to the United States, fleeing the reactionary purges.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Of these, 100 went to the Texas Hill Country as German Texans.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] German Americans would play a major role in the American Civil War.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] More widely, many disillusioned and persecuted revolutionaries, in particular (though not exclusively) those from Germany and the Austrian Empire, left their homelands for foreign exile in the New World or in the more liberal European nations; these emigrants were known as the Forty-Eighters.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Sentiment among German Americans was largely anti-slavery, especially among Forty-Eighters.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] Steven Brust and Emma Bull's 1997 epistolary novel *Freedom & Necessity* is set in England in the aftermath of the Revolutions of 1848.
[src:italy/1848-liberal-revolutions-p02] The 2021 Ukrainian TV series Coffee with Cardamom follows a love-story amid the Revolutions of 1848.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The **1896 Summer Olympics**, officially known as the **Games of the I Olympiad**, and commonly known as **Athens 1896** (Greek: Αθήνα 1896), were the first international Olympic Games held in modern history.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Organised by the International Olympic Committee (IOC), which had been created by French aristocrat Pierre de Coubertin, the event was held in Athens, Greece, from 6 to 15 April 1896.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Fourteen nations (according to the IOC, though the number is subject to interpretation) and 241 athletes (all males; this number is also disputed) took part in the games.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Participants were all European or living in Europe, with the exception of the United States team, and over 65% of the competing athletes were Greek.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Winners were given a silver medal, while runners-up received a copper medal.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Retroactively, the IOC has designated the top three finishers in each event as gold, silver, and bronze medalists.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Ten of the 14 participating nations earned medals.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] On April 6, 1896, American James Connolly became the first Olympic medalist in more than 1,500 years, competing in the triple jump.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The United States won the most gold medals, 11, while host nation Greece won the most medals overall, 47.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The highlight for the Greeks was the marathon victory by their compatriot Spyridon Louis.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The most successful competitor was German wrestler and gymnast Carl Schuhmann, who won four events.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Athens had been chosen to stage the inaugural modern Games during a congress organised by Coubertin in Paris on 23 June 1894, during which the IOC was also created.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The main venue was the Panathenaic Stadium, where athletics and wrestling took place; other venues included the Neo Phaliron Velodrome for cycling and the Zappeion for fencing.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony was held in the Panathenaic Stadium on 6 April, during which most of the competing athletes were aligned on the infield, grouped by nation.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] After a speech by the president of the organising committee, Crown Prince Constantine, his father officially opened the Games.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Afterwards, nine bands and 150 choir singers performed an Olympic Hymn, composed by Spyridon Samaras and written by Kostis Palamas.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The 1896 Olympics were regarded as a great success.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The Games had the largest international participation of any sporting event to that date.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The Panathenaic Stadium overflowed with the largest crowd ever to watch a sporting event.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] After the Games, Coubertin and the IOC were petitioned by several prominent figures, including Greece's King George and some of the American competitors in Athens, to hold all the following Games in Athens.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] However, the 1900 Summer Olympics were already planned for Paris, and, with the exception of the Intercalated Games of 1906, the Olympics did not return to Greece until the 2004 Summer Olympics, 108 years later.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] During the 19th century, several small-scale sports festivals across Europe were named after the ancient Olympic Games.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The 1870 Olympics at the Panathenaic stadium, which had been refurbished for the occasion, had an audience of 30,000 people.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Pierre de Coubertin, a French pedagogue and historian, adopted William Penny Brookes's idea to establish a multi-national and multi-sport event (even though the ancient games only allowed male athletes of Greek origin to participate).
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] In 1890, Coubertin wrote an article in *La Revue Athlétique*, which espoused the importance of Much Wenlock, a rural market town in the English county of Shropshire.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] It was here that, in October 1850, the local physician William Penny Brookes founded the Wenlock Olympian Games, a festival of sports and recreations that included athletics and team sports like cricket, football and quoits.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Coubertin also took inspiration from earlier Greek games organised under the name of Olympics by businessman and philanthropist Evangelis Zappas in 1859, 1870 and 1875.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The 1896 Athens Games were funded by the legacies of Zappas and his cousin Konstantinos Zappas and by George Averoff who had been requested by the Greek government to sponsor the second refurbishment of the Panathenaic Stadium.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The Greek government did this despite the cost of refurbishing the stadium in marble already being funded in full by Evangelis Zappas forty years earlier.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] On 18 June 1894, Coubertin organised a congress at the Sorbonne, Paris, to present his plans to representatives of sports societies from 11 countries.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Following his proposal's acceptance by the congress, a date for the first modern Olympic Games was discussed; Coubertin suggested that the Games be held concurrently with the 1900 Universal Exposition of Paris.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Concerned that a six-year waiting period might lessen public interest, congress members opted to hold the inaugural Games in 1896.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] With a date established, members of the congress discussed the selection of a host city.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] It is unknown how Athens was chosen: Coubertin and Demetrius Vikelas's descriptions of the selection process contradicted the congress's official minutes.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Most accounts state that several congressmen first proposed London, but Coubertin dissented.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] After a brief discussion with Vikelas, who represented Greece, Coubertin suggested Athens.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Vikelas made the Athens proposal official on 23 June; since Greece had been the original home of the Olympics, the congress unanimously approved the decision.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Vikelas was then elected the first president of the newly established International Olympic Committee (IOC).
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The return of the Olympic Games to Greece was well-received by the Greek public, media, and royal family.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The Crown Prince conferred their patronage to the games.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] However, the country had financial troubles and was in political turmoil.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The country's prime minister frequently alternated between Charilaos Trikoupis and Theodoros Deligiannis during the last years of the 19th century.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] This instability caused Trikoupis and Stephanos Dragoumis, the president of the Zappas Olympic Committee, which had attempted to organise a series of national Olympiads, to believe that Greece could not host the event.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] In late 1894, the organising committee under Stephanos Skouloudis presented a report that the cost of the Games would be three times higher than originally estimated by Coubertin.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] They concluded the Games could not be held and offered their resignation.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] With the prospect of reviving the Olympic games in doubt, Coubertin and Vikelas commenced a campaign to increase the Olympic movement's popularity.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] On 7 January 1895 Vikelas announced that crown prince Constantine would assume the presidency of the organising committee.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] His first responsibility was to raise the funds necessary to host the Games.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] He relied on the patriotism of the Greek people to motivate them to provide the required finances.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Constantine's enthusiasm increased contributions from the Greek public, raising 330,000 drachmas (equivalent to $1,106,157,688 in 2025).
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] A special set of postage stamps was commissioned; the sale of which raised 400,000 drachmas (equivalent to $1,340,797,197 in 2025).
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] At the request of Constantine, businessman George Averoff agreed to pay for the restoration of the Panathenaic Stadium.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] As a tribute to his generosity, a statue of Averoff was constructed and unveiled on 5 April 1896 outside the stadium.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The IOC's first regulation, voted on in 1894, was to allow only amateur athletes to participate in the Olympic Games.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The various contests were thus held under amateur regulations, except for fencing matches.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The rules and regulations were not uniform, so the Organising Committee chose among the codes of the various national athletic associations.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The jury, the referees and the game director bore the same names as in antiquity (*Ephor*, *Helanodic* and *Alitarc*).
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Prince George acted as final referee; according to Coubertin, "his presence gave weight and authority to the decisions of the ephors".
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Women could not compete at the 1896 Summer Olympics because Coubertin felt that their inclusion would be "impractical, uninteresting, unaesthetic and incorrect".
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Seven venues were used for the 1896 Summer Olympics.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Panathenaic Stadium was the main venue, hosting four of the nine sports contested.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The town of Marathon hosted the marathon event and the individual road race events.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Fencing was held at the Zappeion, sport shooting at Kallithea, and tennis at the Athens Lawn Tennis Club.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Swimming was held in the Bay of Zea; it was selected because the organizers of the Games wanted to avoid spending money on constructing a special-purpose swimming venue.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Four of the 1896 venues were reused as competition venues for the 2004 Games.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The velodrome would be renovated into a football stadium in the 1960s and was known as Karaiskakis Stadium.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] This venue was renovated in 2003 for use as a football venue for the 2004 Games.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] During the 2004 Games, Panathinaiko Stadium hosted the archery competitions and was the finish line for the athletic marathon event.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The city of Marathon itself served as the starting point for both marathon events during the 2004 Games.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The Zappeion served as the first home of the organizing committee (ATHOC) for the 2004 Games from 1998 to 1999, and served as the press center for non-accredited media during those Games.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] On Easter Monday 6 April (25 March according to the Julian calendar used in Greece until 1923) the games of the First Olympiad were officially opened.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The Panathenaic Stadium was filled with between 16,000 and 80,000 spectators, including King George I of Greece, his wife Olga, and other members of the royal family.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Most of the competing athletes were aligned on the infield, grouped by nation.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Afterwards, nine bands and 150 choir singers performed an Olympic Hymn, composed by Spyridon Samaras, with words by poet Kostis Palamas.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The first announcements regarding the sporting events to be held featured sports like equestrian and cricket, but these plans were not finalised, and these sports did not make the final program for the Games.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Football is sometimes listed as having been an exhibition or demonstration sport, although whether a football match actually occurred is disputed.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Rowing and sailing events were cancelled on the planned days of competition: sailing due to a lack of special boats in Greece and no foreign entries, and rowing due to poor weather.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The 1896 Summer Olympics programme featured 9 sports encompassing 10 disciplines and 43 events.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The athletics events had the most international field of any of the sports.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The major highlight was the marathon, held for the first time in international competition.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Spyridon Louis, a previously unrecognised water carrier, won the event to become the only Greek athletics champion and a national hero.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Although Greece had been favoured to win the discus and the shot put, the best Greek athletes finished second to American Robert Garrett in both events.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] No world records were set, as few top international competitors had elected to compete and the curves of the track were very tight, making fast times in the running events virtually impossible.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Thomas Burke of the United States won the 100-meter race in 12.0 seconds and the 400-meter race in 54.2 seconds.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Burke was the only one who used the "crouch start" (putting his knee on soil), confusing the jury.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Chile claims one athlete, Luis Subercaseaux, who competed for the nation at the 1896 Summer Olympics.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Subercaseaux's results are not listed in the official report, though that report typically includes only winners and Subercaseaux won no medals.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] He was entered to compete in the 100m, 400m and 800m events but is usually listed as a no show.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] An appraisal of a photo of series 2 of the 100 meters sprint, performed by facial recognition experts of the Chilean forensic police, concluded that Subercaseaux was one of the participants.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The day after the official marathon, Stamata Revithi ran the 40-kilometer course in 5 hours 30 minutes, finishing outside Panathinaiko Stadium.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Some authors, who believe that "Melpomene" and Revithi are the same person, attribute to the latter the more favorable time of 4+1⁄2 hours.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] She was denied entry into the official race as the 1896 Olympics excluded women from competition.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The cycling competitions used the rules of the International Cycling Association.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The newly built Neo Phaliron Velodrome hosted the track cycling events.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Only one road event was held, a race from Athens to Marathon and back (87 kilometres).
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] In the track events, the best cyclist was Frenchman Paul Masson, who won the one lap time trial, the sprint event, and the 10,000 meters.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] In the 100 kilometres event, Masson entered as a pacemaker for his compatriot Léon Flameng.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Flameng won the event, after a fall and after stopping to wait for his Greek opponent Georgios Kolettis to fix a mechanical problem.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The Austrian fencer Adolf Schmal won the 12-hour race, which was completed by only two cyclists, while the road race event was won by Aristidis Konstantinidis.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The fencing events were held in the Zappeion, which, built with money Evangelis Zappas had given to revive the ancient Olympic Games, had never seen any athletic contests before.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Unlike other sports (in which only amateurs were allowed to take part at the Olympics), professionals were authorised to compete in fencing, though in a separate event.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] These masters professionals were considered gentlemen athletes, just like the amateurs.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Four events were scheduled, but the épée event was cancelled for unknown reasons.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The foil event was won by a Frenchman, Eugène-Henri Gravelotte, who beat his countryman, Henri Callot, in the final.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The other two events were won by Greek fencers: Ioannis Georgiadis won the sabre event, and Leonidas Pyrgos won the masters foil, becoming the first Greek Olympic champion in the modern era.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The gymnastics competition was carried out on the infield of the Panathinaiko Stadium.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Germany sent an 11-man team, which won five of the eight events, including both team events: in the team event on the horizontal bar, the German team was the only entry.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Three Germans added individual titles: Hermann Weingärtner won the horizontal bar event, Alfred Flatow won the parallel bars, and Carl Schuhmann, who also won the wrestling event, won the vault.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Louis Zutter, a Swiss gymnast, won the pommel horse, while Greeks Ioannis Mitropoulos and Nikolaos Andriakopoulos were victorious in the rings and rope climbing events, respectively.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] A regatta of sailing boats was on the program of the Games of the First Olympiad for 31 March 1896 (Julian calendar).
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The event was cancelled: the official English report blamed a lack of specialty boats had not been provided while the German version also cited a lack of foreign competitors.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Rowing races were scheduled for the next day, 1 April 1896 (Julian).
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Poor weather caused the event to be postponed to 3 pm and German Berthold Küttner stated that he and Adolf Jäger had lined up for the start of the double sculls, the first event to take place.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The event was further postponed to the next day, but the German team still completed the event in the bad weather: they were presented with the winners medal upon the completion of their row.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The next day, the event was formally cancelled when the weather worsened.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee does not recognize Küttner's recollection of the events.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Held at a range at Kallithea, the shooting competition consisted of five events—two using a rifle and three with a pistol.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The first event, the military rifle, was won by Pantelis Karasevdas, the only competitor to hit the target with all of his shots.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The second event, for military pistols, was dominated by two American brothers: John and Sumner Paine.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] They became the first siblings to finish first and second in the same event.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] To avoid embarrassing their hosts, the brothers decided that John would withdraw from the free pistol event.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Sumner Paine won that event, becoming the first relative of an Olympic champion to become Olympic champion himself.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The Paine brothers did not compete in the 25-meter pistol event, as the event judges determined that their weapons were not of the required calibre; Ioannis Phrangoudis won the event.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The final event, the free rifle, could not be completed due to darkness and was finalised the next morning, with Georgios Orphanidis winning the competition.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The swimming competition was held in the open sea because the organizers had refused to spend the money necessary for a specially constructed stadium.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Nearly 20,000 spectators lined the Bay of Zea off the Piraeus coast to watch the events.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The water in the bay was cold, and the competitors suffered during their races.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] There were three open events (men's 100-metre freestyle, men's 500-metre freestyle, and men's 1200 metre freestyle), in addition to a special event open only to Greek sailors, all of which were held on the same day (11 April).
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] For Alfréd Hajós of Hungary, this meant he could only compete in two of the events, as they were held too close together, which made it impossible for him to adequately recuperate.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Nevertheless, he won the two events in which he swam, the 100 and 1200 meter freestyle.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Hajós later became one of only two Olympians to win a medal in both the athletic and artistic competitions, when he won a silver medal for architecture in 1924.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The 500-meter freestyle was won by Austrian swimmer Paul Neumann, who defeated his opponents by more than a minute and a half.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Although tennis was already a major sport by the end of the 19th century, none of the top players turned up for the tournament in Athens.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The competition was held at the courts of the Athens Lawn Tennis Club, and the infield of the velodrome used for the cycling events.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] John Pius Boland, who won the event, had been entered in the competition by a fellow-student of his at Oxford; the Greek, Konstantinos Manos.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] As a member of the Athens Lawn Tennis sub-committee, Manos had been trying, with the assistance of Boland, to recruit competitors for the Athens Games from among the sporting circles of Oxford University.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] In the first round, Boland defeated Friedrich Traun, a promising tennis player from Hamburg, who had been eliminated in the 100-meter sprint competition.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Boland and Traun decided to team up for the doubles event, in which they reached the final and defeated their Greek opponents after losing the first set.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The sport of weightlifting was still young in 1896, and the rules differed from those in use today.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Competitions were held outdoors, in the infield of the main stadium, and there were no weight limits.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The first event was similar in style to what is now known as the "clean and jerk".
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Two competitors stood out: Briton Launceston Elliot and Viggo Jensen of Denmark.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Both of them lifted the same weight, but the jury, with Prince George as the chairman, ruled that Jensen had done so in a better style.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The British delegation, unfamiliar with this tie-breaking rule, lodged a protest.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The lifters were eventually allowed to make further attempts, but neither lifter improved, and Jensen was declared the champion.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Elliot got his revenge in the one hand lift event, which was held immediately after the two-handed one.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Jensen had been slightly injured during his last two-handed attempt and was no match for Elliot, who won the competition easily.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The Greek audience was charmed by the British victor, whom they considered very attractive.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] A curious incident occurred during the weightlifting event: a servant was ordered to remove the weights, which appeared to be a difficult task for him.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Prince George came to his assistance; he picked up the weight and threw it a considerable distance with ease, to the delight of the crowd.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] No weight classes existed for the wrestling competition, held in the Panathenaic Stadium, which meant that there would only be one winner among competitors of all sizes.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The rules used were similar to modern Greco-Roman wrestling, although there was no time limit, and not all leg holds were forbidden (in contrast to current rules).
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Apart from the two Greek contestants, all the competitors had previously been active in other sports.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Weightlifting champion Launceston Elliot faced gymnastics champion Carl Schuhmann.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The latter won and advanced into the final, where he met Georgios Tsitas, who had previously defeated Stephanos Christopoulos.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Darkness forced the final match to be suspended after 40 minutes; it was continued the following day, when Schuhmann needed only fifteen minutes to finish the bout.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] On the morning of Sunday 12 April (or 31 March, according to the Julian calendar then used in Greece), King George organised a banquet for officials and athletes (even though some competitions had not yet been held).
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] During his speech, he made clear that, as far as he was concerned, the Olympics should be held in Athens permanently.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The official closing ceremony was held the following Wednesday after being postponed from Tuesday due to rain.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Again, the royal family attended the ceremony, which was opened by the national anthem of Greece and an ode composed in ancient Greek by George S.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Robertson, a British athlete and scholar.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Afterwards, the king awarded prizes to the winners.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Unlike today, the first-place winners received a silver medal, an olive branch and a diploma, while runners-up received a copper medal, a laurel branch and a diploma.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Third place winners did not receive a prize.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Some winners also received additional prizes.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Spyridon Louis received a cup from Michel Bréal, a friend of Coubertin, who had conceived the marathon event.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Louis then led the medalists on a lap of honour around the stadium, while the Olympic Hymn was played again.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The King then formally announced that the first Olympiad was at an end and left the Stadium, while the band played the Greek national hymn and the crowd cheered.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Like the Greek king, many others supported the idea of holding the next Games in Athens; most of the American competitors signed a letter to the Crown Prince expressing this wish.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Coubertin, however, was heavily opposed to this idea, as he envisioned international rotation as one of the cornerstones of the modern Olympics.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] According to his wish, the next Games were held in Paris, although they would be somewhat overshadowed by the concurrent Universal Exposition.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The concept of national teams was not a major part of the Olympic movement until the Intercalated Games 10 years later, though many sources list the nationality of competitors in 1896 and give medal counts.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] There are significant conflicts with regard to which nations competed.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee gives a figure of 14, but does not list them.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Different sources provide differing lists of nations; some exclude countries like Chile and Bulgaria, but the IOC lists competitors from both countries.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Egypt is also sometimes included due to the participation of Dimitrios Kasdaglis; however, the IOC classifies him as a Greek athlete.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Belgium and Russia had entered the names of competitors, but no athletes from these countries competed.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] National Olympic Committees did not yet exist.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] Ten of the fourteen participating nations earned medals, in addition to two medals won by mixed teams (teams made up of athletes from multiple nations).
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The IOC has retroactively assigned gold, silver and bronze medals to the three best placed athletes in each event to comport with more recent traditions.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] In this regard, five of the bronze medalists at the Games are unknown: two in swimming and three in gymnastics.
[src:italy/1896-summer-olympics] The United States won the most gold medals (11), while host nation Greece won the most medals overall (47), as well as the most silver (18) and bronze (19) medals, finishing with one fewer gold medal than the United States.
[src:italy/18th-century-french-art] In France, the death of Louis XIV in September 1715 led to a period of licentious freedom commonly called the Régence.
[src:italy/18th-century-french-art] The heir to Louis XIV, his great-grandson Louis XV, was only 5 years old; for the next seven years France was ruled by the regent Philippe II, Duke of Orléans.
[src:italy/18th-century-french-art] Versailles was abandoned from 1715 to 1722.
[src:italy/18th-century-french-art] Painting turned toward "fêtes galantes", theater settings and the female nude.
[src:italy/18th-century-french-art] Painters from this period include Antoine Watteau, Nicolas Lancret, and François Boucher.
[src:italy/18th-century-french-art] The Louis XV style of decoration (although already apparent at the end of the last reign) was lighter: pastels and wood panels, smaller rooms, less gilding and fewer brocades; shells and garlands and occasional Chinese subjects predominated.
[src:italy/18th-century-french-art] After the return to Versailles, many of the baroque rooms of Louis XIV were redesigned.
[src:italy/18th-century-french-art] The official etiquette was also simplified and the notion of privacy was expanded: the king himself retreated from the official bed at night and conversed in private with his mistress.
[src:italy/18th-century-french-art] The latter half of the 18th century continued to see French preeminence in Europe, particularly through the arts and sciences, and the French language was the lingua franca of the European courts.
[src:italy/18th-century-french-art] The French academic system continued to produce artists, but some, like Jean-Honoré Fragonard and Jean-Baptiste-Siméon Chardin, explored new and increasingly impressionist styles of painting with thick brushwork.
[src:italy/18th-century-french-art] Although the hierarchy of genres continued to be respected officially, genre painting, landscape, portrait and still life were extremely fashionable.
[src:italy/18th-century-french-art] The writer Denis Diderot wrote a number of times on the annual Salons of the Académie of painting and sculpture and his comments and criticisms are a vital document on the arts of this period.
[src:italy/18th-century-french-art] One of Diderot's favorite painters was Jean-Baptiste Greuze.
[src:italy/18th-century-french-art] One also finds in this period a kind of *Pre-romanticism*.
[src:italy/18th-century-french-art] Hubert Robert's images of ruins, inspired by Italian capriccio paintings, are typical in this respect.
[src:italy/18th-century-french-art] So too the change from the rational and geometrical *French garden* (of André Le Nôtre) to the *English garden*, which emphasized (artificially) wild and irrational nature.
[src:italy/18th-century-french-art] One also finds in some of these gardens curious ruins of temples called follies.
[src:italy/18th-century-french-art] The middle of the 18th century saw a turn to Neoclassicism in France, that is to say a conscious use of Greek and Roman forms and iconography.
[src:italy/18th-century-french-art] In painting, the greatest representative of this style is Jacques-Louis David who, mirroring the profiles of Greek vases, emphasized the use of the profile; his subject matter often involved classical history (the death of Socrates, Brutus).
[src:italy/18th-century-french-art] The dignity and subject matter of his paintings were greatly inspired by Nicolas Poussin in the 17th century.
[src:italy/18th-century-french-art] The Louis XVI style of furniture (once again already present in the previous reign) tended toward circles and ovals in chair backs; chair legs were grooved; Greek inspired iconography was used as decoration.
[src:italy/18th-century-french-art] The Greek and Roman subject matters were also often chosen to promote the values of republicanism.
[src:italy/18th-century-french-art] One also finds paintings glorifying the heroes and martyrs of the French revolution, such as David's painting of the assassination of Jean-Paul Marat.
[src:italy/39] Italian telephone numbers are defined by an open telephone numbering plan that assigns subscriber telephone numbers of six to eleven digits.
[src:italy/39] In addition, other short codes are used for special services.
[src:italy/39] The plan is organized by types of services, indicated by the first digit.
[src:italy/39] Geographic landline numbers start with the digit *0*, while mobile telephone numbers start with *3*.
[src:italy/39] Four types of emergency services use three-digit telephone numbers in the group *11X*, including 112 for the Carabinieri.
[src:italy/39] Other initial digits denote other services, such as toll-free numbers.
[src:italy/39] The dialing procedures for callers mandate that the full telephone number is always dialed, including the area code, which is called *prefix* (*prefisso* in Italian).
[src:italy/39] Since 1998, the leading *0* of landline numbers has to be included also when calling from abroad, in contrast with the practice in many other countries.
[src:italy/39] The country code for calling Italy from abroad is *39*.
[src:italy/39] For calling foreign destinations from Italy, the international call prefix is *00*, as is standard in most European countries.
[src:italy/39] Italian regulations prescribe no fixed rules for grouping the digits of telephone numbers for printing or display.
[src:italy/39] Various grouping schemes are commonly used and a telephone number is likely to be written or pronounced differently by different people.
[src:italy/39] Commonly used formatting or punctuation characters include the space character, the dot, full stop, and the hyphen.
[src:italy/39] The minimum length of telephone numbers is three digits and the maximum is twelve.
[src:italy/39] Landline numbers start with the digit *0* and are 6 to 11 digits long, although they are rarely shorter than 9.
[src:italy/39] They are composed of a variable length prefix followed by a variable length subscriber number.
[src:italy/39] Apart from the capital and Milan, which have the sole two-digit codes, principal cities/regions have three-digit codes and smaller towns have four-digit codes.
[src:italy/39] Mobile telephone numbers start with the digit *3* and are generally ten digits long.
[src:italy/39] It is still possible, but rare, to find nine-digit numbers, which were the first to be assigned.
[src:italy/39] The group of the first three digits of a mobile telephone number (*prefix*) identifies the mobile network operator that assigned the number, but since 2002, mobile number portability is possible and thus any number can end up being managed by any carrier.
[src:italy/39] Some network operators allow the caller to insert additional digits for redirecting calls to voice mail.
[src:italy/39] For example, dialing, "**36** 339 7550176" might connect to the voice mail service of the telephone number "339 7550176".
[src:italy/39] The extra digits vary based on the network operator managing the service.
[src:italy/39] Emergency and service numbers start with the digit *1*.
[src:italy/39] Four emergency numbers are currently in use, but a process has been started to consolidate them with *112*, previously assigned to the gendarmerie, already the unique emergency number in some areas.
[src:italy/39] Calls to 112 are answered within seconds and in multiple languages.
[src:italy/39] Special-rate numbers start with *8* and include toll-free numbers (called *green numbers*, *numeri verdi* in Italian, starting with "80..."), shared-rate numbers ("84...") and premium-rate services ("89...").
[src:italy/39] Numbers starting with *4* are used for network-specific phone services like voice mailbox and various information services; they can be free, non-premium or premium.
[src:italy/39] The digit **5** has been reserved for VoIP numbers.
[src:italy/39] Finally **7** is used for internet services such as virtual fax numbers and dial up internet access ("70...").
[src:italy/39] Numbers starting with the digits *2*, *6* and *9* are currently unassigned and reserved for future purposes.
[src:italy/39] In the past it was possible to omit the prefix when calling from a landline to another landline in the same area.
[src:italy/39] The digit "0" was the trunk code and it had to be removed when calling from abroad.
[src:italy/39] This changed in 1998, with a transition period lasting from 19 June to 31 December.
[src:italy/39] The new dialing procedures require dialing the full number for all calls.
[src:italy/39] The main advantage is the availability of millions of previously reserved phone numbers.
[src:italy/39] The change was widely advertised with a campaign named "Fissa il prefisso" ("Attach the prefix").
[src:italy/39] It was originally intended to replace the leading *0* with *4* for landlines.
[src:italy/39] This was scheduled for implementation commencing 29 December 2000, but never happened.
[src:italy/39] Instead, *4* was assigned to identify network services.
[src:italy/39] Until 2001 a leading "0" was part of any mobile phone number, but it has been removed.
[src:italy/39] Several other smaller changes occurred over the years: for example the prefix for toll free numbers changed from "167" to "800" in 1999.
[src:italy/39] The Italian enclave San Marino has its own country code **378**, but landline numbers can be reached using the Italian country code as well: the prefix "0549" is assigned to San Marino.
[src:italy/39] Dialing either "+378 xxxxxx" or "+39 0549 xxxxxx" will reach the same number.
[src:italy/39] Mobile phone customers are sometimes assigned Italian phone numbers.
[src:italy/39] The country code **379** is assigned to Vatican City, but it is not used: telephone numbers in Vatican City are integrated into the Italian numbering plan.
[src:italy/39] Vatican landline telephone numbers are in the form "+39 06 698xxxxx", "+39" being the country code for Italy and "06" the prefix for Rome.
[src:italy/41] The Swiss telephone numbering plan implements the ITU-T recommendation E.164 and is designated E.164/2002, based on its last major revision in 2002.
[src:italy/41] It is a closed numbering plan, which means that all telephone numbers, including the area code, have a fixed number of digits.
[src:italy/41] Swiss area codes are officially termed *national destination codes* (NDC).
[src:italy/41] A complete telephone number consists of ten digits: *0xx xxx xx xx*.
[src:italy/41] Two formats are distinguished: three digits for the NDC and seven digits for the subscriber number, and four digits for the NDC and six digits for the subscriber number.
[src:italy/41] The associated dial plan requires that all numbers, even for local calls, must be dialed with the assigned NDC, in contrast to previous plans.
[src:italy/41] When dialing from within the country, a prefix *0* must be dialed.
[src:italy/41] The plan was amended a few times, e.g., the transition of numbering zone 01 into 044 and 043.
[src:italy/41] The national destination code (NDC) is the area code for Swiss telephone numbers.
[src:italy/41] Within Switzerland the trunk code 0 must be dialed before the NDC, while it is not needed from international locations.
[src:italy/41] Telephone numbers are portable between numbering zones (ZN) or between mobile operators, and therefore an NDC does not imply that a caller is actually located in a particular zone or is serviced by any particular mobile operator.
[src:italy/41] For landlines it is now merely an indication of the region where the number was originally attributed to a subscriber.
[src:italy/41] The national destination codes are the following.
[src:italy/41] Short dialing codes are assigned for special services or network features.
[src:italy/41] Instead of E.164/2002, another more ambitious numbering plan was proposed.
[src:italy/41] In this plan the prefix 0 was discarded, and the area codes were defined differently, with 20 to 49 for geographic areas, 50 to 59 reserved, 60-69 for nationwide numbering, 70-79 for mobile services, 80-89 for shared-cost and toll-free numbers, and 90 for premium-rate services.
[src:italy/41] The plan was not implemented because it required too many phone number and prefix changes, with associated high costs.
[src:italy/41] On 29 March 2002 the Swiss dialing plan changed to a closed dialing plan, i.e. the zone prefix become mandatory also for local calls.
[src:italy/41] The previous plan removed a lot of area prefixes and added the seventh digit in phone numbers (usually a phone number (0cc) yx xx xx became (0dd) zzx xx xx).
[src:italy/41] The German municipality of Büsingen am Hochrhein, an enclave within the canton of Schaffhausen, uses the Swiss telecom network, with numbers having the prefix 052, alongside that of Germany, from which numbers must be dialled in the international format as 004152.
[src:italy/41] The Italian municipality of Campione d'Italia, an exclave within the Swiss canton of Ticino, uses the Swiss telephone network and is part of the Swiss numbering plan, although some Italian numbers are in use by the municipal council, which use the same +39 031 numbering range as the town of Como.
[src:italy/41] Liechtenstein previously used the Swiss telephone numbering plan with the area code 075.
[src:italy/41] (This was dialled as +41 75 from outside Switzerland and Liechtenstein).
[src:italy/41] However, on 5 April 1999, it adopted its own international code +423.
[src:italy/41] Consequently, calls from Switzerland now require international dialling, using the **00423** prefix and the seven-digit number.
[src:italy/it] The first .it domain requested was that of the CNR (National Research Council: cnuce.cnr.it); the request was sent on 23 December 1987, and the domain became active on 1 January 1988.
[src:italy/it] On 23 December 1987, IANA assigned the .it ccTLD to CNUCE, an institute of the CNR in Pisa, and the first name registered was that of the CNR's CNUCE.
[src:italy/it] Policies and rules were agreed with operators in the sector using a variety of forms.
[src:italy/it] After the setting-up of the initial group, called MAIL-ITA, followed by ITA-PE 162 (which held its meetings at the CSELT) in 1994, 1998 saw the establishment of the Italian Naming Authority, which was responsible for drafting the rules for assigning '.it' domains until 2005.
[src:italy/it] This structure differed from the Italian Registration Authority, which was responsible for keeping the Registry of names and made available the technical infrastructure needed to maintain it, thereby also including the management of authoritative DNS delegations.
[src:italy/it] In 1999, the Naming Authority carried out a 'liberalisation' of the ccTLD by removing the limit on the number of domain names that could be registered for organisations of any kind.
[src:italy/it] In the same year, management of the Registry passed to the Institute's Director Franco Denoth.
[src:italy/it] In 2001, a merger of several institutes of the CNR gave rise to the Institute of Informatics and Telematics, which consequently took over responsibility.
[src:italy/it] In 2004, the limit on the number of registrations was also removed for natural persons.
[src:italy/it] As of 2005, the Registry took over both regulatory and implementation functions with the establishment of an internal committee (the Steering Committee) that included representatives of the sector's operators.
[src:italy/it] In 2009, the .it ccTLD Registry changed its name to Registro .it, the registry of Italian domains.
[src:italy/it] Following Denoth's death in April 2006, the direction of the Institute (and thus of Registro) was temporarily taken over by Enrico Gregori on 17 May 2006, followed by Domenico Laforenza in 2008 and Marco Conti in 2019.
[src:italy/it] Currently, the Institute is directed by Andrea Passarella.
[src:italy/it] Since 11 July 2012, it has also been possible to register .it domains with non-ASCII characters (IDN), i.e., special characters, accented letters, etc.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The history of Italy goes back to numerous Italic peoples, notably including the ancient Romans, who conquered the Mediterranean world during the Roman Republic and ruled it for centuries during the Roman Empire.
[src:italy/italy-p01] With the spread of Christianity, Rome became the seat of the Catholic Church and the Papacy.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Barbarian invasions and other factors led to the decline and fall of the Western Roman Empire between late antiquity and the Early Middle Ages.
[src:italy/italy-p01] By the 11th century, Italian city-states and maritime republics expanded, bringing renewed prosperity through commerce and laying the groundwork for modern capitalism.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The Italian Renaissance flourished during the 15th and 16th centuries and spread to the rest of Europe.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Italian explorers discovered new routes to the Far East and the New World, contributing significantly to the Age of Discovery.
[src:italy/italy-p01] After centuries of political and territorial divisions, the Kingdom of Italy was established in 1861, following wars of independence and the Expedition of the Thousand.
[src:italy/italy-p01] From the late 19th to the early 20th century, Italy industrialised and acquired a colonial empire, while the south remained largely impoverished, fuelling a large immigrant diaspora to the Americas.
[src:italy/italy-p01] From 1915 to 1918, Italy took part in World War I with the Entente against the Central Powers.
[src:italy/italy-p01] In 1922, the Italian fascist dictatorship was established.
[src:italy/italy-p01] During World War II, Italy was first part of the Axis until an armistice with the Allied powers (1940–1943), then a co-belligerent of the Allies during the Italian resistance and liberation of Italy from German occupation and the collaborationist RSI (1943–1945).
[src:italy/italy-p01] In 1946, the monarchy was replaced by a republic and the country made a strong recovery.
[src:italy/italy-p01] A developed country with an advanced economy, Italy has the eighth-largest nominal GDP in the world, the second-largest manufacturing sector in Europe, and plays a significant role in regional and – to a lesser extent – global economic, military, cultural, and political affairs.
[src:italy/italy-p01] It is a founding and leading member of the European Union, and is part of numerous other international organisations and forums.
[src:italy/italy-p01] As a cultural superpower, Italy has long been a renowned global centre of art, music, literature, cuisine, fashion, science and technology, and the source of multiple inventions and discoveries.
[src:italy/italy-p01] It has the highest number of World Heritage Sites (61) and is the fourth most visited country in the world by international tourist arrivals.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Hypotheses for the etymology of *Italia* are numerous.
[src:italy/italy-p01] One theory suggests it originated from an Ancient Greek term for the land of the *Italói*, a tribe that resided in the region now known as Calabria.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Originally thought to be named *Vituli*, some scholars suggest their totemic animal to be the calf (Latin: *vitulus*; Umbrian: *vitlo*; Oscan: *Víteliú*).
[src:italy/italy-p01] Several ancient authors said it was named after a local ruler Italus.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The ancient Greek term for Italy initially referred only to the south of the Bruttium peninsula and parts of Catanzaro and Vibo Valentia.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The larger concept of Oenotria and "Italy" became synonymous, and the name applied to most of Lucania as well.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Before the Roman Republic's expansion, the name was used by Greeks for the land between the strait of Messina and the line connecting the gulfs of Salerno and Taranto, corresponding to Calabria.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The Greeks came to apply "Italia" to a larger region.
[src:italy/italy-p01] In addition to the "Greek Italy" in the south, historians have suggested the existence of an "Etruscan Italy", which consisted of areas of central Italy.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The borders of Roman Italy, *Italia*, are better established.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Cato's *Origines* describes Italy as the entire peninsula south of the Alps.
[src:italy/italy-p01] In 264 BC, Roman Italy extended from the Arno and Rubicon rivers of the centre-north to the entire south.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The northern area, Cisalpine Gaul, considered geographically part of Italy, was occupied by Rome in the 220s BC, but remained politically separated.
[src:italy/italy-p01] It was legally merged into the administrative unit of Italy in 42 BC.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Sardinia, Corsica, Sicily, and Malta were added to Italy by Diocletian in 292 AD, which made late-ancient Italy coterminous with the modern Italian geographical region.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The Latin *Italicus* was used to describe "a man of Italy" as opposed to a *provincial*, or one from the Roman province.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The adjective *italianus*, from which *Italian* was derived, is from medieval Latin and was used alternatively with *Italicus* during the early modern period.
[src:italy/italy-p01] After the fall of the Western Roman Empire, the Ostrogothic Kingdom of Italy was created.
[src:italy/italy-p01] After the Lombard invasions, *Italia* was retained as the name for their kingdom, and its successor kingdom within the Holy Roman Empire.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Lower Paleolithic artefacts, dating back 850,000 years, have been recovered from Monte Poggiolo.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Excavations throughout Italy revealed a Neanderthal presence in the Middle Palaeolithic period 200,000 years ago, while modern humans appeared about 40,000 years ago at Riparo Mochi.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The ancient peoples of pre-Roman Italy were Indo-European, specifically the Italic peoples.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The main historic peoples of possible non-Indo-European or pre-Indo-European heritage include the Etruscans, the Elymians and Sicani of Sicily, and the prehistoric Sardinians, who gave birth to the Nuragic civilisation.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Other ancient populations include the Rhaetian people and Camunni, known for their rock drawings in Valcamonica.
[src:italy/italy-p01] A natural mummy, Ötzi, dated 3400–3100 BC, was discovered in the Similaun glacier in 1991.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The first colonisers were the Phoenicians, who established emporiums on the coasts of Sicily and Sardinia.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Some became small urban centres and developed parallel to Greek colonies.
[src:italy/italy-p01] During the 8th and 7th centuries, Greek colonies were established at Pithecusae, eventually extending along the south of the Italian Peninsula and the coast of Sicily, an area later known as Magna Graecia.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Ionians, Doric colonists, Syracusans, and the Achaeans founded various cities.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Greek colonisation placed the Italic peoples in contact with democratic forms of government and high artistic and cultural expressions.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Italy's history goes back to numerous Italic peoples – notably including the ancient Romans, who conquered the Mediterranean world during the Roman Republic and ruled it for centuries during the Roman Empire.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Ancient Rome, a settlement on the River Tiber in central Italy, founded in 753 BC, was ruled for 244 years by a monarchical system.
[src:italy/italy-p01] In 509 BC, the Romans, favouring a government of the Senate and the People (SPQR), expelled the monarchy and established an oligarchic republic.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The Italian Peninsula, named *Italia*, was consolidated into a unified entity during Roman expansion, the conquest of new territories often at the expense of the other Italic tribes, Etruscans, Celts, and Greeks.
[src:italy/italy-p01] A permanent association, with most of the local tribes and cities, was formed, and Rome began the conquest of Western Europe, North Africa, and the Middle East.
[src:italy/italy-p01] In the wake of Julius Caesar's assassination in 44 BC, Rome grew into a massive empire stretching from Britain to the borders of Persia, engulfing the whole Mediterranean basin, in which Greek, Roman, and other cultures merged into a powerful civilisation.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The long reign of the first emperor, Augustus, began an age of peace and prosperity.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Roman Italy remained the metropole of the empire, homeland of the Romans and territory of the capital.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The first two centuries of the empire saw a period of unprecedented stability known as the Pax Romana (lit.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Rome reached its greatest territorial extent under Trajan (r.
[src:italy/italy-p01] 98–117 AD), but a period of increasing trouble and decline began under Commodus (r.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The Migration Period, involving large invasions by Germanic peoples, led to the decline of the Roman Empire.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The Roman Empire was among the largest in history, wielding great economical, cultural, political, and military power.
[src:italy/italy-p01] At its greatest extent, it had an area of 5 million square kilometres (1.9 million square miles).
[src:italy/italy-p01] The Roman legacy has deeply influenced Western civilisation shaping the modern world.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The widespread use of Romance languages derived from Latin, numerical system, modern Western alphabet and calendar, and the emergence of Christianity as a world religion, are among the many legacies of Roman dominance.
[src:italy/italy-p01] After the fall of the Western Roman Empire, Italy fell under the Odoacer's kingdom, and was seized by the Ostrogoths.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Invasions resulted in a chaotic succession of kingdoms and the supposed "Dark Ages".
[src:italy/italy-p01] The invasion of another Germanic tribe in the 6th century, the Lombards, reduced Byzantine presence and ended the political unity of the peninsula.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The north formed the Lombard kingdom, central-south was also controlled by the Lombards, and other parts remained Byzantine.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The Lombard kingdom was absorbed into Francia by Charlemagne in the late 8th century and became the Kingdom of Italy.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The Franks helped form the Papal States.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Until the 13th century, politics was dominated by relations between the Holy Roman Emperors and the Papacy, with city-states siding with the former (Ghibellines) or with the latter (Guelphs) for momentary advantage.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The Germanic emperor and Roman pontiff became the universal powers of medieval Europe.
[src:italy/italy-p01] However, conflict over the Investiture controversy and between Guelphs and Ghibellines ended the imperial-feudal system in the north, where cities gained independence.
[src:italy/italy-p01] In 1176, the Lombard League of city-states defeated Holy Roman Emperor Frederick Barbarossa, ensuring their independence.
[src:italy/italy-p01] City-states, such as Milan, Florence, and Venice, played a crucially innovative role in financial development by devising banking practices, and enabling new forms of social organisation.
[src:italy/italy-p01] In coastal and southern areas, maritime republics dominated the Mediterranean and monopolised trade to the Orient.
[src:italy/italy-p01] They were independent thalassocratic city-states, in which merchants had considerable power.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Although oligarchical, the relative political freedom they afforded was conducive to academic and artistic advancement.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The best-known maritime republics were Venice, Genoa, Pisa, and Amalfi.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Each had dominion over overseas lands, islands, lands on the Adriatic, Aegean, and Black seas, and commercial colonies in the Near East and North Africa.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Venice and Genoa were Europe's gateways to the East, and producers of fine glass, while Florence was a centre of silk, wool, banking, and jewellery.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The wealth generated enabled the commissioning of large public and private artistic projects.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The republics participated in the Crusades, providing support and transport but primarily pursuing political and commercial opportunities.
[src:italy/italy-p01] In the south, Sicily had become an Arab Islamic emirate in the 9th century, thriving until the Italo-Normans conquered it in the late 11th century, together with most of the Lombard and Byzantine principalities of southern Italy.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The region was subsequently divided between the Kingdom of Sicily and Kingdom of Naples.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The Black Death of 1348 killed perhaps a third of Italy's population.
[src:italy/italy-p01] During the 1400s and 1500s, Italy was the birthplace and heart of the Renaissance.
[src:italy/italy-p01] This era marked the transition from the medieval period to the modern age and was fostered by the wealth accumulated by merchant cities and the patronage of dominant families.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Italian polities transitioned into regional states ruled by princes who controlled trade and administration, while their courts became prominent centres of the arts and sciences.
[src:italy/italy-p01] These princedoms were led by political dynasties and merchant families, such as the Medici of Florence.
[src:italy/italy-p01] After the end of the Western Schism, newly elected Pope Martin V returned to the Papal States and restored Italy as the sole centre of Western Christianity.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The Medici Bank was made the credit institution of the Papacy, and significant ties were established between the Church and new political dynasties.
[src:italy/italy-p01] In 1453, despite activity by Pope Nicholas V to support the Byzantines, the city of Constantinople fell to the Ottomans.
[src:italy/italy-p01] This led to the migration of Greek scholars and texts to Italy, fuelling the rediscovery of Greek humanism.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Humanist rulers such as Federico da Montefeltro and Pope Pius II worked to establish ideal cities, founding Urbino and Pienza.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Pico della Mirandola wrote the *Oration on the Dignity of Man*, considered the manifesto of the Renaissance.
[src:italy/italy-p01] In the arts, the Italian Renaissance exercised a dominant influence on European art for centuries, with artists such as Leonardo da Vinci, Botticelli, Michelangelo, Raphael, Giotto, Donatello, and Titian, and architects such as Filippo Brunelleschi, Andrea Palladio, and Donato Bramante.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Italian explorers and navigators from the maritime republics, eager to find an alternative route to the Indies to bypass the Ottomans, offered their services to monarchs of Atlantic countries and played a key role in ushering the Age of Discovery and colonisation of the Americas.
[src:italy/italy-p01] A defensive alliance known as the Italic League was formed between Venice, Naples, Florence, Milan, and the Papacy.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Lorenzo *the Magnificent* de Medici was the Renaissance's greatest patron, his support allowed the League to abort invasion by the Turks.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The alliance, however, collapsed in the 1490s; the invasion of Charles VIII of France initiated a series of wars in the peninsula.
[src:italy/italy-p01] During the High Renaissance, popes such as Julius II (1503–1513) fought for control of Italy against foreign monarchs; Paul III (1534–1549) preferred to mediate between the European powers to secure peace.
[src:italy/italy-p01] In the middle of such conflicts, the Medici popes Leo X (1513–1521) and Clement VII (1523–1534) faced the Protestant Reformation in Germany, England and elsewhere.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The Papacy launched the Counter-Reformation, whose key events include: the Council of Trent (1545–1563); adoption of the Gregorian calendar; the Jesuit China mission; the French Wars of Religion; end of the Thirty Years' War (1618–1648); and the Great Turkish War.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The Italian economy declined in the 1600s and 1700s.
[src:italy/italy-p01] During the War of the Spanish Succession (1700–1714), Austria acquired most of the Spanish domains in Italy, namely Milan, Naples and Sardinia; the latter was given to the House of Savoy in exchange for Sicily in 1720.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Later, a branch of the Bourbons ascended to the throne of Sicily and Naples.
[src:italy/italy-p01] During the Napoleonic Wars, north and central Italy were reorganised as Sister Republics of France and, later, as a Kingdom of Italy.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The south was administered by Joachim Murat, Napoleon's brother-in-law.
[src:italy/italy-p01] 1814's Congress of Vienna restored the situation of the late 18th century, but the ideals of the French Revolution could not be eradicated, and re-surfaced during the political upheavals that characterised the early 19th century.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The first adoption of the Italian tricolour by an Italian state, the Cispadane Republic, occurred during Napoleonic Italy, following the French Revolution, which advocated national self-determination.
[src:italy/italy-p01] This event is celebrated by Tricolour Day.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The birth of the Kingdom of Italy was the result of efforts of Italian nationalists and monarchists loyal to the House of Savoy to establish a united kingdom encompassing the entire Italian Peninsula.
[src:italy/italy-p01] By the mid-19th century, rising Italian nationalism led to revolution.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Following the Congress of Vienna in 1815, the political and social Italian unification movement, or Risorgimento, emerged to unite Italy by consolidating the states and liberating them from foreign control.
[src:italy/italy-p01] A radical figure was the patriotic journalist Giuseppe Mazzini, founder of the political movement Young Italy in the 1830s, who favoured a unitary republic and advocated a broad nationalist movement.
[src:italy/italy-p01] 1847 saw the first public performance of "Il Canto degli Italiani", which became the national anthem in 1946.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The most famous member of Young Italy was the revolutionary and general Giuseppe Garibaldi who led the republican drive for unification in southern Italy.
[src:italy/italy-p01] However, the Italian monarchy of the House of Savoy, in the Kingdom of Sardinia, whose government was led by Camillo Benso, Count of Cavour, also had ambitions of establishing a united Italian state.
[src:italy/italy-p01] In the context of the 1848 liberal revolutions that swept Europe, an unsuccessful First Italian War of Independence was declared against Austria.
[src:italy/italy-p01] In 1855, Sardinia became an ally of Britain and France in the Crimean War.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Sardinia fought the Austrian Empire in the Second Italian War of Independence of 1859, with the aid of France, resulting in liberating Lombardy.
[src:italy/italy-p01] On the basis of the Plombières Agreement, the Sardinia ceded Savoy and Nice to France, an event that caused the Niçard exodus.
[src:italy/italy-p01] In 1860–1861, Garibaldi led the drive for unification in Naples and Sicily.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Teano was the site of a famous meeting between Garibaldi and Victor Emmanuel II, the last king of Sardinia, during which Garibaldi shook Victor Emanuel's hand and hailed him as King of Italy.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Cavour agreed to include Garibaldi's southern Italy in a union with the Kingdom of Sardinia in 1860.
[src:italy/italy-p01] This allowed the Sardinian government to declare a united Italian kingdom on 17 March 1861, with Victor Emmanuel II as its first king.
[src:italy/italy-p01] In 1865, the kingdom's capital was moved from Turin to Florence.
[src:italy/italy-p01] In 1866, Victor Emmanuel II, allied with Prussia during the Austro-Prussian War, waged the Third Italian War of Independence, which resulted in Italy annexing Venetia.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Finally, in 1870, as France abandoned Rome during the Franco-Prussian War, the Italians captured the Papal States, unification was completed, and the capital moved to Rome.
[src:italy/italy-p01] (right), leading figures in unification, became respectively the first King and prime minister of unified Italy.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Sardinia's constitution was extended to all of Italy in 1861, and provided basic freedoms for the new state; but electoral laws excluded the non-propertied classes.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The new kingdom was governed by a parliamentary constitutional monarchy dominated by liberals.
[src:italy/italy-p01] As northern Italy quickly industrialised, southern and northern rural areas remained underdeveloped and overpopulated, forcing millions to migrate and fuelling a large and influential diaspora.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The Italian Socialist Party increased in strength, challenging the traditional liberal and conservative establishment.
[src:italy/italy-p01] In the last two decades of the 19th century, Italy developed into a colonial power by subjugating Eritrea, Somalia, Tripolitania, and Cyrenaica in Africa.
[src:italy/italy-p01] In 1913, male universal suffrage was adopted.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The pre-World War I period was dominated by Giovanni Giolitti, prime minister five times between 1892 and 1921.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Italy entered into the First World War in 1915 with the aim of completing national unity, so it is also considered the Fourth Italian War of Independence, from a historiographical perspective, as the conclusion of the unification of Italy.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The country's contribution to the Allied victory earned it a place as one of the "Big Four" powers.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Reorganisation of the army and conscription led to Italian victories.
[src:italy/italy-p01] In October 1918, the Italians launched a massive offensive, culminating in victory at the Battle of Vittorio Veneto.
[src:italy/italy-p01] This marked the end of war on the Italian Front, secured dissolution of the Austro-Hungarian Empire, and was instrumental in ending the war less than two weeks later.
[src:italy/italy-p01] During the war, more than 650,000 Italian soldiers and as many civilians died, and the kingdom was on the brink of bankruptcy.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The Treaty of Saint-Germain-en-Laye (1919) and Treaty of Rapallo (1920) allowed for annexation of Trentino and South Tyrol, the Julian March, Istria, the Kvarner Gulf, and the Dalmatian city of Zara.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The subsequent Treaty of Rome (1924) led to annexation of Fiume by Italy.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Italy did not receive other territories promised by the Treaty of London, so this outcome was denounced as a "mutilated victory", by Benito Mussolini, which helped lead to the rise of Italian fascism.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Historians regard "mutilated victory" as a "political myth", used by fascists to fuel Italian imperialism.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Italy gained a permanent seat in the League of Nations's executive council.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The socialist agitations that followed the devastation of the Great War, inspired by the Russian Revolution, led to counter-revolution and repression throughout Italy.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The liberal establishment, fearing a Soviet-style revolution, started to endorse the small National Fascist Party, led by Mussolini.
[src:italy/italy-p01] In October 1922, the Blackshirts of the National Fascist Party organised a mass demonstration and the "March on Rome" coup.
[src:italy/italy-p01] King Victor Emmanuel III appointed Mussolini as prime minister, transferring power to the fascists without armed conflict.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Mussolini banned political parties and curtailed personal liberties, establishing a dictatorship.
[src:italy/italy-p01] These actions attracted international attention and inspired similar dictatorships in Nazi Germany and Imperial Japan.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Fascism was based upon Italian nationalism and imperialism, seeking to expand Italian possessions via irredentist claims based on the legacy of the Roman and Venetian empires.
[src:italy/italy-p01] For this reason, the fascists engaged in interventionist foreign policy.
[src:italy/italy-p01] In 1935, Mussolini invaded Ethiopia and founded Italian East Africa, resulting in international isolation.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Italy withdrew from the League of Nations.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Italy then allied with Nazi Germany and the Empire of Japan, and strongly supported Francisco Franco in the Spanish Civil War.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Italy entered World War II on 10 June 1940.
[src:italy/italy-p01] At this date, France practically had lost the Battle of France.
[src:italy/italy-p01] At different times, Italians advanced in British Somaliland, Egypt, the Balkans, and eastern fronts.
[src:italy/italy-p01] They were, however, defeated on the Eastern Front as well as in the East African and North African campaigns, losing their territories in Africa and the Balkans.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Italian war crimes included extrajudicial killings and ethnic cleansing by deportation of about 25,000 people – mainly Yugoslavs – to Italian concentration camps and elsewhere.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Yugoslav Partisans perpetrated their own crimes against the ethnic Italian population during and after the war, including the foibe massacres.
[src:italy/italy-p01] An Allied invasion of Sicily began in July 1943, leading to the collapse of the Fascist regime on 25 July.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Mussolini was deposed and arrested by order of King Victor Emmanuel III.
[src:italy/italy-p01] On 3 September, Italy signed the Armistice of Cassibile, ending its war with UK and USA.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The Germans, with the assistance of Italian fascists, succeeded in taking control of north and central Italy (Operation Achse).
[src:italy/italy-p01] The country remained a battlefield, with the Allies moving up from the south.
[src:italy/italy-p01] In the north, the Germans set up the Italian Social Republic (RSI), a Nazi puppet state and collaborationist regime with Mussolini installed as leader after he was rescued by German paratroopers.
[src:italy/italy-p01] What remained of the Italian troops was organised into the Italian Co-belligerent Army, which fought alongside the Allies, while other Italian forces, loyal to Mussolini, opted to fight alongside the Germans in the National Republican Army.
[src:italy/italy-p01] German troops, with RSI collaboration, committed massacres and deported thousands of Jews to death camps.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The post-armistice period saw the emergence of the Italian Resistance, who fought a guerrilla war against the Nazi German occupiers and collaborators.
[src:italy/italy-p01] An aspect of this period was the Italian civil war due to fighting between partisans and fascist RSI forces.
[src:italy/italy-p01] In April 1945, with defeat looming, Mussolini attempted to escape north, but was captured and summarily executed by partisans.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Hostilities ended on 29 April 1945, when the German forces in Italy surrendered.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Nearly half a million Italians died in the war, society was divided, and the economy all but destroyed – per capita income in 1944 was at its lowest point since 1900.
[src:italy/italy-p01] In the aftermath of the war there was a revival of Italian republicanism, leading to the 1946 Italian institutional referendum.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Italy became a republic after the 1946 referendum held on 2 June, a day celebrated since as *Festa della Repubblica*.
[src:italy/italy-p01] This was the first time women voted nationally.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Victor Emmanuel III's son, Umberto II, was forced to abdicate.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The Republican Constitution was approved in 1948.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Under the Treaty of Paris between Italy and the Allied Powers, areas next to the Adriatic Sea were annexed by Yugoslavia, resulting in the Istrian-Dalmatian exodus, which involved the emigration of around 300,000 Istrian and Dalmatian Italians.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Italy lost all colonial possessions, ending the Italian Empire.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Fears of a Communist takeover proved crucial in 1948, when the Christian Democrats, under Alcide De Gasperi, won a landslide victory.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Consequently, in 1949 Italy became a member of NATO.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The Marshall Plan revived the economy, which, until the late 1960s, enjoyed a period called the Italian economic miracle.
[src:italy/italy-p01] In the 1950s, Italy became a founding country of the European Communities, a forerunner of the European Union.
[src:italy/italy-p01] From the late 1960s until the early 1980s, the country experienced the *Years of lead*, characterised by economic difficulties, especially after the 1973 oil crisis; social conflicts; and terrorist massacres.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The economy recovered and Italy became the world's fifth-largest industrial nation after it gained entry into the G7 in the 1970s.
[src:italy/italy-p01] However, national debt skyrocketed past 100% of GDP.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Between 1992 and 1993, Italy faced terror attacks perpetrated by the Sicilian Mafia as a consequence of new anti-mafia measures by the government.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Voters – disenchanted with political paralysis, massive public debt, and extensive corruption uncovered by the Clean Hands investigation – demanded radical reform.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The Christian Democrats, who had ruled for almost 50 years, underwent a crisis and disbanded, splitting into factions.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The Communists reorganised as a social-democratic force.
[src:italy/italy-p01] During the 1990s and 2000s, centre-right (dominated by media magnate Silvio Berlusconi) and centre-left coalitions (led by professor Romano Prodi) alternately governed.
[src:italy/italy-p01] In the early 21st century, Italy experienced a prolonged period of political and economic instability, strongly influenced by international crises.
[src:italy/italy-p01] During the 2010s, efforts were made by new prime minister Matteo Renzi to introduce institutional reforms intended to streamline the political system and strengthen the executive branch, though these initiatives were rejected by a referendum in 2016.
[src:italy/italy-p01] At the same time, the European migrant crisis placed Italy in a central role as a major point of entry into the European Union via the Mediterranean, resulting in a large inflow of migrants and asylum seekers, particularly from sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:italy/italy-p01] This development had notable social and political consequences, contributing to growing public debate over immigration and leading to a surge in support for populist parties.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The COVID-19 pandemic, which began in 2020, severely affected the country's public health and economic performance, exacerbating pre-existing structural weaknesses.
[src:italy/italy-p01] In response, extraordinary measures were adopted to support the economy, many of them coordinated at the European level.
[src:italy/italy-p01] In 2022, Giorgia Meloni was sworn in as Italy's first female prime minister.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Italy, whose territory largely coincides with the eponymous geographical region, is located in Southern Europe (and is also considered part of Western Europe) between latitudes 35° and 47° N, and longitudes 6° and 19° E.
[src:italy/italy-p01] To the north, from west to east, Italy borders France, Switzerland, Austria, and Slovenia, and is roughly delimited by the Alpine watershed, enclosing the Po Valley and the Venetian Plain.
[src:italy/italy-p01] It consists of the entirety of the Italian Peninsula, Sicily and Sardinia (the biggest islands of the Mediterranean), and many smaller islands.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Some of Italy's territory extends beyond the Alpine basin, and some islands are located outside the Eurasian continental shelf.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Including the islands, Italy has a coastline of 7,600 kilometres (4,722 miles) on the Mediterranean Sea, the Ligurian and Tyrrhenian seas, the Ionian Sea, and the Adriatic Sea.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The sovereign states of San Marino and Vatican City (the smallest country in the world and headquarters of the worldwide Catholic Church under the governance of the Holy See) are enclaves within Italy, while Campione d'Italia is an Italian exclave in Switzerland.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The border with San Marino is 39 km (24 mi) long; that with Vatican City is 3.2 km (2.0 mi).
[src:italy/italy-p01] Over 35% of Italian territory is mountainous.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The Apennine Mountains form the peninsula's backbone, and the Alps form most of its northern boundary, where Italy's highest point is located on the summit of Mont Blanc (*Monte Bianco*) at 4,810 m (15,780 ft).
[src:italy/italy-p01] Other well-known mountains include the Matterhorn (*Monte Cervino*) in the western Alps, and the Dolomites in the eastern Alps.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Many parts of Italy are of volcanic origin.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Most small islands and archipelagos in the south are volcanic islands.
[src:italy/italy-p01] There are active volcanoes: Mount Etna in Sicily (the largest in Europe), Vulcano, Stromboli, and Vesuvius.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Most rivers of Italy drain into the Adriatic or Tyrrhenian Sea.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The longest is the Po, which flows from the Alps on the western border, and crosses the Padan plain to the Adriatic.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The Po Valley is the largest plain, with 46,000 km2 (18,000 sq mi), and contains over 70% of the country's lowlands.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The largest lakes are, in descending size: Garda (367.94 km2 or 142 sq mi), Maggiore (212.51 km2 or 82 sq mi), and Como (145.9 km2 or 56 sq mi).
[src:italy/italy-p01] Italy's climate is influenced by the seas that surround the country on every side except the north, which constitute a reservoir of heat and humidity.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Within the southern temperate zone, they determine a Mediterranean climate with local differences.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Because of the length of the peninsula and the mostly mountainous hinterland, the climate is highly diverse.
[src:italy/italy-p01] In most inland northern and central regions, the climate ranges from humid subtropical to humid continental and oceanic.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The Po Valley is mostly humid subtropical, with cool winters and hot summers.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The coastal areas of Liguria, Tuscany, and most of the south generally fit the Mediterranean climate stereotype, as in the Köppen climate classification.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Conditions on the coast are different from those in the interior, particularly during winter when the higher altitudes tend to be cold, wet, and often snowy.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The coastal regions have mild winters, and hot and generally dry summers; lowland valleys are hot in summer.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Winter temperatures vary from 0 °C (32 °F) in the Alps to 12 °C (54 °F) in Sicily; so, average summer temperatures range from 20 °C (68 °F) to over 25 °C (77 °F).
[src:italy/italy-p01] Winters can vary widely with lingering cold, foggy, and snowy periods in the north, and milder, sunnier conditions in the south.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Summers are hot across the country, except at high altitude, particularly in the south.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Northern and central areas can experience strong thunderstorms from spring to autumn.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Italy's varied geography, including the Alps, Apennines, central Italian woodlands, and southern Italian Garigue and Maquis shrubland, contribute to habitat diversity.
[src:italy/italy-p01] As the peninsula is in the centre of the Mediterranean, forming a corridor between Central Europe and North Africa, and having 8,000 km (5,000 mi) of coastline, Italy has received species from the Balkans, Eurasia, and the Middle East.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Italy has probably the highest level of faunal biodiversity in Europe, with over 57,000 species recorded, representing more than a third of all European fauna, and the highest level of biodiversity of animal and plant species within the EU.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The fauna of Italy includes 4,777 endemic animal species, which include the Sardinian long-eared bat, Sardinian red deer, spectacled salamander, brown cave salamander, Italian newt, Italian frog, Apennine yellow-bellied toad, Italian wall lizard, and Sicilian pond turtle.
[src:italy/italy-p01] There are 119 mammals species, 550 bird species, 69 reptile species, 39 amphibian species, 623 fish species, and 56,213 invertebrate species, of which 37,303 are insect species.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The flora of Italy was traditionally estimated to comprise about 5,500 vascular plant species.
[src:italy/italy-p01] However, as of 2005, 6,759 species are recorded in the *Data bank of Italian vascular flora*.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Italy has 1,371 endemic plant species and subspecies, which include Sicilian fir, Barbaricina columbine, Sea marigold, Lavender cotton, and Ucriana violet.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Italy is a signatory to the Berne Convention on the Conservation of European Wildlife and Natural Habitats and the Habitats Directive.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Italy has many botanical and historic gardens.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The Italian garden is stylistically based on symmetry, axial geometry, and the principle of imposing order on nature.
[src:italy/italy-p01] It influenced the history of gardening, especially French and English gardens.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The Italian garden was influenced by Roman and Italian Renaissance gardens.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The Italian wolf is the national animal of Italy, while the national tree is the strawberry tree.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The national bird is the Italian sparrow, while the national flower is the flower of the strawberry tree.
[src:italy/italy-p01] After its quick industrial growth, Italy took time to address its environmental problems.
[src:italy/italy-p01] After improvements, Italy now ranks 84th in the world for ecological sustainability.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The total area protected by national parks, regional parks, and nature reserves covers about 11% of Italian territory, and 12% of Italy's coastline is protected.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Italy has been one of the world's leading producers of renewable energy, in 2010 ranking as the fourth largest provider of installed solar energy capacity and sixth largest of wind power capacity.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Renewable energy provided approximately 37% Italy's energy consumption in 2020.
[src:italy/italy-p01] The country operated nuclear reactors between 1963 and 1990 but, after the Chernobyl disaster and referendums, the nuclear programme was terminated, a decision overturned by the government in 2008, with plans to build up to four nuclear power plants.
[src:italy/italy-p01] This was in turn struck down by a referendum following the Fukushima nuclear accident.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Air pollution remains severe, especially in the industrialised north.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Italy is the twelfth-largest carbon dioxide producer.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Extensive traffic and congestion in large cities continue to cause environmental and health issues, even if smog levels have decreased since the 1970s and 1980s, with smog becoming an increasingly rare phenomenon and levels of sulphur dioxide decreasing.
[src:italy/italy-p01] Deforestation, illegal building, and poor land-management policies have led to significant erosion in Italy's mountainous regions, leading to ecological disasters such as the 1963 Vajont Dam flood, the 1998 Sarno, and the 2009 Messina mudslides.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Italy has been a unitary parliamentary republic since 1946, when the monarchy was abolished.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The president of Italy, Sergio Mattarella since 2015, is Italy's head of state.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The president is elected for a single seven-year term by the Italian Parliament and regional voters in joint session.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Italy has a written democratic constitution that resulted from a Constituent Assembly formed by representatives of the anti-fascist forces that contributed to the defeat of Nazi and Fascist forces during the liberation of Italy, in World War II.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Italy plays a major role in several economic, military, cultural, and political affairs, and is one of the EU big three.
[src:italy/italy-p02] It is widely considered to be a regional power, while its great power status is a subject of debate among scholars and political analysts.
[src:italy/italy-p02] According to International IDEA's Global State of Democracy (GSoD) Indices and Democracy Tracker, Italy performs in the high range on overall democratic measures, with particular weaknesses in rule of law.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Italy has a parliamentary government based on a mixed-member majoritarian representation system.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The parliament is perfectly bicameral; each house has the same powers.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The two houses: the Chamber of Deputies meets in Palazzo Montecitorio, and the Senate of the Republic in Palazzo Madama.
[src:italy/italy-p02] A peculiarity of the Italian Parliament is the representation given to Italian citizens permanently living abroad: 8 Deputies and 4 Senators are elected in four distinct overseas constituencies.
[src:italy/italy-p02] There are senators for life, appointed by the president "for outstanding patriotic merits in the social, scientific, artistic or literary field".
[src:italy/italy-p02] Former presidents are *ex officio* life senators.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The prime minister of Italy is head of government and has executive authority, but must receive a vote of approval from the Council of Ministers to execute most policies.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The prime minister and cabinet are appointed by the president, and confirmed by a vote of confidence in parliament.
[src:italy/italy-p02] To remain as prime minister, one has to pass votes of confidence.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The role of prime minister is similar to most other parliamentary systems, but they are not authorised to dissolve parliament.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The major political parties are the Brothers of Italy, Democratic Party, and Five Star Movement.
[src:italy/italy-p02] During the 2022 general election, these three and their coalitions won 357 of the 400 seats in the Chamber of Deputies, and 187 of 200 in the Senate.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The centre-right coalition, which included Giorgia Meloni's Brothers of Italy, Matteo Salvini's League, Silvio Berlusconi's Forza Italia, and Maurizio Lupi's Us Moderates, won most seats in parliament.
[src:italy/italy-p02] These are hierarchical: the law or regulation from a lower source cannot conflict with the rule of an upper source (hierarchy of sources).
[src:italy/italy-p02] The Constitution of 1948 is the highest source.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The Constitutional Court of Italy rules on the conformity of laws with the constitution.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The judiciary bases their decisions on Roman law modified by the Napoleonic Code and later statutes.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The Supreme Court of Cassation is the highest court for both criminal and civil appeals.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Italy lags behind other Western European nations in LGBT rights.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Italy's law prohibiting torture is considered behind international standards.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Law enforcement is complex with multiple police forces.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The national policing agencies are the Polizia di Stato ('State Police'), the Carabinieri, the Guardia di Finanza ('Financial Police'), and the Polizia Penitenziaria ('Prison Police'), as well as the Guardia Costiera ('Coast Guard Police').
[src:italy/italy-p02] Although policing is primarily provided on a national basis, there are also the provincial and municipal police.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Since their appearance in the middle of the 19th century, Italian organised crime and criminal organisations have infiltrated the social and economic life of many regions in southern Italy; the most notorious is the Sicilian Mafia, which expanded into foreign countries, including the US.
[src:italy/italy-p02] A 2009 report identified 610 *comuni* which have a strong Mafia presence, where 13 million Italians live and 15% of GDP is produced.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The Calabrian 'Ndrangheta, probably the most powerful crime syndicate of Italy, accounts alone for 3% of GDP.
[src:italy/italy-p02] At 0.013 per 1,000 people, Italy has the 47th highest murder rate, compared to 61 countries, and the 43rd highest number of rapes per 1,000 people, compared to 64 countries in the world.
[src:italy/italy-p02] These are relatively low figures among developed countries.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Italy is a founding member of the European Economic Community (EEC), now the European Union (EU), and of NATO.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Its turns in the rotating presidencies of international organisations include the Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe in 2018, G7 in 2017, and the EU Council in 2014.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Italy is a recurrent non-permanent member of the UN Security Council.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Italy strongly supports multilateral international politics, endorsing the UN and its international security activities.
[src:italy/italy-p02] In 2013, Italy had 5,296 troops deployed abroad, engaged in 33 UN and NATO missions in 25 countries.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Italy deployed troops in support of UN peacekeeping missions in Somalia, Mozambique, and East Timor.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Italy provides support for NATO and UN operations in Bosnia, Kosovo, and Albania, and deployed over 2,000 troops to Afghanistan in support of Operation Enduring Freedom (OEF) from 2003.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Italy supported international efforts to reconstruct and stabilise Iraq, but it had withdrawn its military contingent of 3,200 troops by 2006.
[src:italy/italy-p02] In August 2006, Italy deployed about 2,450 troops for the United Nations Interim Force in Lebanon.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Italy is one of the largest financiers of the Palestinian Authority, contributing €60 million in 2013 alone.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The Italian Army, Navy, Air Force, and Carabinieri collectively form the Italian Armed Forces, under the command of the High Council of Defence, presided over by the president, per the Constitution of Italy.
[src:italy/italy-p02] According to Article 78, the Parliament has the authority to declare a state of war and vest the necessary war-making powers in the government.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Despite not being a branch of the armed forces, the Guardia di Finanza has military status and is organised along military lines.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Since 2005, military service has been voluntary.
[src:italy/italy-p02] In 2010, the Italian military had 293,202 personnel on active duty, of which 114,778 are Carabinieri.
[src:italy/italy-p02] As part of NATO's nuclear sharing strategy, Italy hosts 90 US B61 nuclear bombs located at the Ghedi and Aviano air bases.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The Army is the national ground defence force.
[src:italy/italy-p02] It was formed in 1946, when Italy became a republic, from what remained of the "Royal Italian Army".
[src:italy/italy-p02] Its best-known combat vehicles are the Dardo infantry fighting vehicle, the B1 Centauro tank destroyer, and the Ariete tank, and among its aircraft are the Mangusta attack helicopter, deployed on EU, NATO, and UN missions.
[src:italy/italy-p02] It has at its disposal Leopard 1 and M113 armoured vehicles.
[src:italy/italy-p02] It was also formed in 1946 from what remained of the *Regia Marina* (the 'Royal Navy').
[src:italy/italy-p02] As a member of the EU and NATO, the Navy has participated in coalition peacekeeping operations worldwide.
[src:italy/italy-p02] In 2014, the Navy operated 154 vessels in service, including minor auxiliary vessels.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The Italian Air Force was founded as an independent service arm in 1923 by King Victor Emmanuel III as the *Regia Aeronautica* ('Royal Air Force').
[src:italy/italy-p02] After World War II, it was renamed as the *Aeronautica Militare*.
[src:italy/italy-p02] In 2021, the Italian Air Force operated 219 combat jets.
[src:italy/italy-p02] A transport capability is guaranteed by a fleet of 27 C-130Js and C-27J Spartan.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The acrobatic display team is the *Frecce Tricolori* ('Tricolour Arrows').
[src:italy/italy-p02] An autonomous corps of the military, the Carabinieri are the gendarmerie and military police of Italy, policing the military and civilian population alongside Italy's other police forces.
[src:italy/italy-p02] While different branches of the Carabinieri report to separate ministries, the corps reports to the Ministry of Internal Affairs when maintaining public order and security.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Italy is constituted of 20 regions (*regioni*), five of which have special autonomous status which enables them to enact legislation on additional matters.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The *regioni* contain 107 provinces (*province*) or metropolitan cities (*città metropolitane*), and 7,896 municipalities (*comuni*).
[src:italy/italy-p02] Italy has an advanced mixed economy that is the third-largest in the eurozone and 11th-largest in the world by purchasing power parity-adjusted GDP.
[src:italy/italy-p02] It possesses the ninth-largest national wealth and ranks third in central bank gold reserves.
[src:italy/italy-p02] As a founding member of the G7, the eurozone, and the OECD, it is one of the most industrialised countries and a major trading nation in Europe; as of 2024, it exported €612 billion in goods and had a trade surplus of €46 billion.
[src:italy/italy-p02] A developed country ranked 30th on the Human Development Index, Italy performs well in life expectancy, healthcare, and education.
[src:italy/italy-p02] It is well known for its creative and innovative businesses, a competitive agricultural sector, and its influential and high-quality automobile, machinery, food, design, and fashion industries.
[src:italy/italy-p02] This has produced a niche-markets manufacturing sector often focused on the export of luxury products.
[src:italy/italy-p02] While less capable of competing on quantity, it can compete with Asian economies that have lower labour costs through higher-quality products.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Italy was the world's 9th-largest exporter in 2023.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Its closest trade ties are with other EU countries, and its largest export partners in 2019 were Germany (12%), France (11%), and the US (10%).
[src:italy/italy-p02] The Italian automotive industry is a significant part of the country's manufacturing sector, with over 144,000 firms and almost 485,000 employees in 2015, contributing 9% to GDP.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The country boasts a wide range of vehicles, from mass market-oriented brands such as Fiat and premium brands like Alfa Romeo and Maserati to luxury supercars such as Pagani, Lamborghini, and Ferrari.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The Banca Monte dei Paschi di Siena is the world's oldest or second oldest bank in continuous operation, depending on the definition, and the fourth-largest Italian commercial and retail bank.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Italy has a strong cooperative sector with the largest share in the EU of the population (4.5%) employed by a cooperative.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The Val d'Agri area, Basilicata, hosts the largest onshore hydrocarbon field in Europe.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Moderate natural gas reserves, mainly in the Po Valley and offshore under the Adriatic, have been discovered and constitute the country's most important mineral resource.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Italy is one of the world's leading producers of pumice, pozzolana, and feldspar.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Another notable resource is marble, especially the famous white Carrara marble from Tuscany.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Italy is part of a monetary union, the eurozone, which represents around 330 million citizens, and of the European single market, which represents more than 500 million consumers.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Several domestic commercial policies are determined by agreements among EU members and EU legislation.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Italy joined the common European currency, the euro, in 2002.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Its monetary policy is set by the European Central Bank.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Italy was hit by the 2008 financial crisis, which exacerbated structural problems.
[src:italy/italy-p02] After strong GDP growth of 5–6% per year from the 1950s to the early 1970s, and a progressive slowdown in the 1980–90s, the country stagnated in the 2000s.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Political efforts to revive growth with massive government spending produced a severe rise in public debt, which stood at over 132% of GDP in 2017; the second highest in the EU, after Greece.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The largest portion of Italian public debt is owned by national subjects, a major difference between Italy and Greece, and the level of household debt is much lower than the OECD average.
[src:italy/italy-p02] A gaping north–south divide is a major factor of socio-economic weakness; there is a huge difference in official income between northern and southern regions and municipalities.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The richest province, Alto Adige-South Tyrol, earns 152% of the national GDP per capita, while the poorest region, Calabria, earns 61%.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The unemployment rate (11%) is above the eurozone average, but the disaggregated figure is 7% in the north and 19% in the south.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The median disposable income was $27,949 per year in 2021 (PPP).
[src:italy/italy-p02] The youth unemployment rate (32% in 2018) is extremely high.
[src:italy/italy-p02] According to the last agricultural census, there were 1.6 million farms in 2010 (−32% since 2000) covering 12,700,000 ha or 31,382,383 acres (63% are in south Italy).
[src:italy/italy-p02] 99% are family-operated and small, averaging only 8 ha (20 acres).
[src:italy/italy-p02] Of the area in agricultural use, grain fields take up 31%, olive orchards 8%, vineyards 5%, citrus orchards 4%, sugar beets 2%, and horticulture 2%.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The remainder is primarily dedicated to pastures (26%) and feed grains (12%).
[src:italy/italy-p02] Italy is the world's largest wine producer, and a leading producer of olive oil, fruits (apples, olives, grapes, oranges, lemons, pears, apricots, hazelnuts, peaches, cherries, plums, strawberries, and kiwifruits), and vegetables (especially artichokes and tomatoes).
[src:italy/italy-p02] The most famous Italian wines are the Tuscan Chianti and the Piedmontese Barolo.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Other famous wines are Barbaresco, Barbera d'Asti, Brunello di Montalcino, Frascati, Montepulciano d'Abruzzo, Morellino di Scansano, and the sparkling wines Franciacorta and Prosecco.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Quality goods in which Italy specialises, particularly wines and regional cheeses, are often protected under the quality assurance labels DOC/DOP.
[src:italy/italy-p02] This geographical indication certificate, accredited by the EU, is considered important to avoid confusion with ersatz goods.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Italy was the first country to build motorways, the *autostrade*, reserved for fast traffic and motor vehicles.
[src:italy/italy-p02] In 2002 there were 668,721 km (415,524 mi) of serviceable roads in Italy, including 6,487 km (4,031 mi) of motorways, state-owned but privately operated by Atlantia.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The railway network, state-owned, managed by Rete Ferroviaria Italiana (RFI), a subsidiary of Ferrovie dello Stato Italiane (FSI), as of December 2025 totalled 16,881 km (10,489 mi), of which 12,364 km (7,683 mi) is electrified, and on which 4,802 locomotives and railcars run.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The main public operator of high-speed trains is Trenitalia, part of FSI.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Italy has 11 rail border crossings over the Alpine mountains with neighbouring countries.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Italy is fifth in Europe by number of passengers using air transport, with about 148 million passengers, or about 10% of the European total in 2011.
[src:italy/italy-p02] In 2022, there were 45 civil airports, including the hubs of Milan Malpensa Airport and Rome Fiumicino Airport.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Since 2021, Italy's flag carrier has been ITA Airways, which took over from Alitalia.
[src:italy/italy-p02] In 2004, there were 43 major seaports, including Genoa, the country's largest and second-largest in the Mediterranean.
[src:italy/italy-p02] In 2005, Italy maintained a civilian air fleet of about 389,000 units and a merchant fleet of 581 ships.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The national inland waterways network had a length of 2,400 km (1,491 mi) for commercial traffic in 2012.
[src:italy/italy-p02] North Italian ports, such as the deep-water port of Trieste, with its extensive rail connections to Central and Eastern Europe, are the destination of subsidies and significant foreign investment.
[src:italy/italy-p02] In August 2025, the planned Strait of Messina Bridge was given final approval by the Meloni government, with construction set to commence in the autumn of 2025.
[src:italy/italy-p02] It will connect Calabria with Sicily when it opens in 2032, and it will become the longest suspension bridge in the world.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Italy has become one of the world's largest producers of renewable energy, ranking as the second largest producer in the EU and the ninth in the world.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Wind power, hydroelectricity, and geothermal power are significant sources of electricity in the country.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Renewable sources account for 28% of all electricity produced, with hydro alone reaching 13%, followed by solar at 6%, wind at 4%, bioenergy at 3.5%, and geothermal at 1.6%.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The rest of the national demand is supplied by fossil fuels (natural gas 38%, coal 13%, oil 8%) and imports.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Eni, operating in 79 countries, is one of the seven "Big Oil" companies, and one of the world's largest industrial companies.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Solar energy production alone accounted for 9% of electricity in 2014, making Italy the country with the highest contribution from solar energy in the world.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The Montalto di Castro Photovoltaic Power Station, completed in 2010, is the largest photovoltaic (PV) power station in Italy.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Italy was the first country to exploit geothermal energy to produce electricity.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Nuclear power in Italy was abandoned after 1987 referendums (in the wake of the 1986 Chernobyl disaster), although Italy still imports nuclear energy from Italy-owned reactors in foreign territories.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Through the centuries, Italy has fostered a scientific community that produced major discoveries the sciences.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Galileo Galilei played a major role in the Scientific Revolution and is widely considered the father of observational astronomy, modern physics, and the scientific method.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The Laboratori Nazionali del Gran Sasso (LNGS) is the largest underground research centre in the world.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Trieste has the highest percentage of researchers in Europe, in relation to the population.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Italy was ranked 28th in the Global Innovation Index in 2025.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The north–south large difference in income leads to a "digital divide".
[src:italy/italy-p02] People have visited Italy for centuries, yet the first to visit the peninsula for tourism were aristocrats during the Grand Tour, which began in the 17th century, and flourished in the 18th and the 19th centuries.
[src:italy/italy-p02] This was a period in which European aristocrats, many of whom were British, visited parts of Europe, with Italy as a key destination.
[src:italy/italy-p02] For Italy, this was to study ancient architecture, local culture, and admire its natural beauty.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Italy is the second-most visited country, with a total of 74 million arrivals in 2024, behind Spain.
[src:italy/italy-p02] In 2014, the income from travel and tourism was EUR163 billion (10% of GDP) and 1,082,000 jobs were directly related to it (5% of employment).
[src:italy/italy-p02] Tourist interest is mainly in culture, cuisine, history, architecture, art, religious sites and routes, wedding tourism, naturalistic beauties, nightlife, underwater sites, and spas.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Winter and summer tourism are present in locations in the Alps and the Apennines, while seaside tourism is widespread among locations along the Mediterranean.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Italy is the leading cruise tourism destination in the Mediterranean.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Small, historical, and artistic villages are promoted through the association I Borghi più belli d'Italia (lit.
[src:italy/italy-p02] 'The most beautiful villages of Italy').
[src:italy/italy-p02] The most visited regions are Veneto, Tuscany, Lombardy, Emilia-Romagna, and Lazio.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Rome is the third most visited city in Europe, and 12th in the world, with 9.4 million arrivals in 2017.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Venice and Florence are among the world's top 100 destinations.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Italy has the most World Heritage Sites of any country: 61, of which 55 are cultural and 6 natural.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Its population density of 195 inhabitants per square kilometre (510/sq mi) is higher than most Western European countries.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Italy's population almost doubled during the 20th century, but the pattern of growth was uneven because of large-scale internal migration from the rural south to the industrial north, a consequence of the Italian economic miracle of the 1950–1960s.
[src:italy/italy-p02] High fertility rates persisted until the 1970s, after which they started to decline; the total fertility rate (TFR) reached an all-time low of 1.2 children per woman in 1995, well below the replacement rate of 2.1 and considerably below the high of 5 in 1883.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Since 2008, when the rate climbed slightly to 1.4, the number of births has consistently declined every year, reaching a record low of 379,000 in 2023 – the fewest since 1861.
[src:italy/italy-p02] As a result of these trends, Italy's population is rapidly aging and gradually shrinking.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Nearly one in four Italians is over 65, and the country has the fourth oldest population in the world, with a median age of 48 and an average age of 46.6.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The overall population has been falling steadily since 2014 and is estimated to have fallen just below 59 million in 2024, representing a cumulative loss of more than 1.36 million people in one decade.
[src:italy/italy-p02] From the late 19th century to the 1960s, Italy was a country of mass emigration.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Between 1898 and 1914, the peak years of Italian diaspora, approximately 750,000 Italians emigrated annually.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The diaspora included more than 25 million Italians and is considered the greatest mass migration of recent times.
[src:italy/italy-p02] In the 1980s, until then a linguistically and culturally homogeneous society, Italy began to attract substantial flows of immigrants.
[src:italy/italy-p02] After the fall of the Berlin Wall and of the Iron Curtain, waves of migration originated from many former socialist countries of East Europe.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The EU enlarged in 2004, in 2007 (Romania and Bulgaria), and in 2013 (Croatia).
[src:italy/italy-p02] Other sources of immigration have been neighbouring North Africa, the Asia-Pacific region, the Philippines and Latin America.
[src:italy/italy-p02] In 2010, the foreign-born population was from the following regions: Europe (54%), Africa (22%), Asia (16%), the Americas (8%), and Oceania (0.06%).
[src:italy/italy-p02] The distribution of the foreign population is geographically varied: in 2020, 61% of foreign citizens lived in the north, 24% in the centre, 11% in the south, and 4% on the islands.
[src:italy/italy-p02] In 2021, Italy had about 5.2 million foreign residents, making up 9% of the population.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The figures include more than half a million children born in Italy to foreign nationals, but exclude foreign nationals who have subsequently acquired Italian citizenship; in 2016, about 201,000 people became Italian citizens.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The official figures also do not include illegal immigrants, which was estimated to be 670,000 in 2008.
[src:italy/italy-p02] About one million Romanian citizens are registered as living in Italy, representing the largest migrant population.
[src:italy/italy-p02] There are an estimated 64 million native Italian speakers around the world, and another 21 million use it as a second language.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Italian is often natively spoken as a regional dialect, not to be confused with Italy's regional and minority languages; however, during the 20th century, the establishment of a national education system led to a decrease in regional dialects.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Standardisation was further expanded in the 1950s and 1960s, due to economic growth and the rise of mass media and television.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Twelve "historical minority languages" are formally recognised: Albanian, Catalan, German, Greek, Slovene, Croatian, French, Franco-Provençal, Friulian, Ladin, Occitan, and Sardinian.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Four of these enjoy co-official status in their respective regions: French in the Aosta Valley; German in South Tyrol, and Ladin as well in some parts of the same province and in parts of the neighbouring Trentino; and Slovene in the provinces of Trieste, Gorizia, and Udine.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Other Ethnologue, ISO, and UNESCO languages are not recognised under Italian law.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Like France, Italy has signed the European Charter for Regional or Minority Languages, but has not ratified it.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Due to recent immigration, Italy has sizeable populations whose native language is not Italian, nor a regional language.
[src:italy/italy-p02] According to the Italian National Institute of Statistics, in 2012 Romanian was the most common mother tongue among foreign residents: almost 800,000 people speak Romanian as their first language (22% of foreign residents aged 6 and over).
[src:italy/italy-p02] Other prevalent mother tongues were Arabic (spoken by over 475,000; 13% of foreign residents), Albanian (380,000), and Spanish (255,000).
[src:italy/italy-p02] The Holy See, the episcopal jurisdiction of Rome, contains the government of Vatican City and the worldwide Catholic Church.
[src:italy/italy-p02] It is recognised as a sovereign entity, headed by the pope, who is also the Bishop of Rome, with which diplomatic relations can be maintained.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Italy has historically been dominated by Catholicism.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Most Catholics are nominal; Associated Press described Italian Catholicism as "nominally embraced but rarely lived".
[src:italy/italy-p02] Around 2010, Italy had the world's fifth-largest Catholic population and the largest in Europe.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Since 1985, Catholicism is no longer the state religion.
[src:italy/italy-p02] In 2011, minority Christian faiths included an estimated 1.5 million Orthodox Christians, while Protestantism has been growing.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Italy has for centuries welcomed Jews expelled from other countries, notably Spain.
[src:italy/italy-p02] However, about 20% of Italian Jews were killed during the Holocaust.
[src:italy/italy-p02] This, together with emigration before and after World War II, has left around 28,000 Jews.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The state devolves shares of income tax to recognised religious communities, under a regime known as eight per thousand.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Donations are allowed to Christian, Jewish, Buddhist, and Hindu communities; however, Islam remains excluded, as no Muslim communities have signed a concordat.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Taxpayers who do not wish to fund a religion contribute their share to the welfare system.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Education is mandatory and free from ages six to sixteen, and consists of five stages: kindergarten, primary school, lower secondary school, upper secondary school, and university.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Students are given a basic education in Italian, English, mathematics, natural sciences, history, geography, social studies, physical education, and visual and musical arts.
[src:italy/italy-p02] In 2018, secondary education was evaluated as being below the average among OECD countries.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Italy scored below the OECD average in reading and science, and near the OECD average in mathematics.
[src:italy/italy-p02] A wide gap exists between northern schools, which perform near average, and the south, which had much poorer results.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Tertiary education is divided between public universities, private universities, and the prestigious and selective superior graduate schools, such as the Scuola Normale Superiore di Pisa.
[src:italy/italy-p02] 33 Italian universities were ranked among the world's top 500 in 2019.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Bologna University, founded in 1088, is the oldest university still in operation, and one of the leading academic institutions in Europe.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Bocconi University, the Università Cattolica del Sacro Cuore, LUISS, the Polytechnic University of Turin, the Polytechnic University of Milan, the Sapienza University of Rome, and the University of Milan are also ranked among the best.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Italy's life expectancy in 2015 was 80.5 years for men and 84.8 for women, placing the country 5th in the world.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Compared to other Western countries, Italy has a low rate of adult obesity (below 10%), as the health benefits of the Mediterranean diet are very significant.
[src:italy/italy-p02] In 2013, UNESCO, prompted by Italy, added the Mediterranean diet to the Representative List of the Intangible Cultural Heritage of Humanity of Italy, Morocco, Spain, Portugal, Greece, Cyprus, and Croatia.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The proportion of daily smokers was 22% in 2012, down from 24% in 2000 but above the OECD average.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Since 2005, smoking in public places has been restricted to "specially ventilated rooms".
[src:italy/italy-p02] Since 1978, the state has run a universal public healthcare system.
[src:italy/italy-p02] However, healthcare is provided to all citizens and residents by a mixed public-private system.
[src:italy/italy-p02] The public part is the Servizio Sanitario Nazionale, which is organised under the Ministry of Health and administered on a devolved regional basis.
[src:italy/italy-p02] Healthcare spending accounted for 10% of GDP in 2020.
[src:italy/italy-p03] Italy is one of the primary birthplaces of Western civilisation and a cultural superpower.
[src:italy/italy-p03] Its culture has been shaped by a multitude of regional customs and local centres of power and patronage.
[src:italy/italy-p03] The country has made substantial contributions to the cultural and historical heritage of Europe.
[src:italy/italy-p03] The first to begin a recognised sequence of designs were the Greeks and the Etruscans, progressing to classical Roman, then the revival of the classical Roman era during the Renaissance, and evolving into the Baroque era.
[src:italy/italy-p03] The Christian concept of the basilica, a style that came to dominate in the Middle Ages, was invented in Rome.
[src:italy/italy-p03] Romanesque architecture, which flourished from approximately 800 to 1100 AD, was one of the most fruitful and creative periods in Italian architecture, when masterpieces, such as the Leaning Tower of Pisa and the Basilica of Sant'Ambrogio in Milan, were built.
[src:italy/italy-p03] It was known for its usage of Roman arches, stained glass windows, and curved columns.
[src:italy/italy-p03] The main innovation of Italian Romanesque architecture was the vault, which had never been seen in Western architecture.
[src:italy/italy-p03] Italian architecture significantly evolved during the Renaissance.
[src:italy/italy-p03] Filippo Brunelleschi contributed to architectural design with his dome for the Cathedral of Florence, a feat of engineering not seen since antiquity.
[src:italy/italy-p03] A popular achievement of Italian Renaissance architecture was St.
[src:italy/italy-p03] Peter's Basilica, designed by Donato Bramante in the early 16th century.
[src:italy/italy-p03] Andrea Palladio influenced architects throughout Western Europe with the villas and palaces he designed.
[src:italy/italy-p03] The Baroque period produced outstanding Italian architects.
[src:italy/italy-p03] The most original work of late Baroque and Rococo architecture is the Palazzina di caccia of Stupinigi.
[src:italy/italy-p03] In 1752, Luigi Vanvitelli began the construction of the Royal Palace of Caserta.
[src:italy/italy-p03] In the late 18th and early 19th centuries, Italy was influenced by the Neoclassical architectural movement.
[src:italy/italy-p03] Villas, palaces, gardens, interiors, and art began again to be based on ancient Roman and Greek themes.
[src:italy/italy-p03] During the Fascist period, the supposedly "Novecento movement" flourished, based on the rediscovery of imperial Rome.
[src:italy/italy-p03] Marcello Piacentini, responsible for the urban transformations of cities, devised a form of simplified Neoclassicism.
[src:italy/italy-p03] The history of Italian visual arts is significant to Western painting.
[src:italy/italy-p03] Roman art was influenced by Greece and can be taken as a descendant of ancient Greek painting.
[src:italy/italy-p03] The only surviving Roman paintings are wall paintings.
[src:italy/italy-p03] These may contain the first examples of trompe-l'œil, pseudo-perspective, and pure landscape.
[src:italy/italy-p03] The Italian Renaissance is considered to be a golden age of painting, spanning from the 15th to the late 16th centuries and having significant influence outside Italy.
[src:italy/italy-p03] Artists such as Masaccio, Filippo Lippi, Tintoretto, Sandro Botticelli, Leonardo da Vinci, Michelangelo, Raphael, and Titian took painting to a higher level through the use of perspective.
[src:italy/italy-p03] Michelangelo was also active as a sculptor; his works include masterpieces such as *David*, *Pietà*, and *Moses*.
[src:italy/italy-p03] In the 15th and 16th centuries, the High Renaissance gave rise to a stylised art known as Mannerism.
[src:italy/italy-p03] In place of the balanced compositions and rational approach to perspective that characterised art at the dawn of the 16th century, the Mannerists sought instability, artifice, and doubt.
[src:italy/italy-p03] The unperturbed faces and gestures of Piero della Francesca and the calm Virgins of Raphael were replaced by the troubled expressions of Pontormo and emotional intensity of El Greco.
[src:italy/italy-p03] In the 17th century, among the greatest painters of Italian Baroque are Caravaggio, Artemisia Gentileschi, Carlo Saraceni, and Bartolomeo Manfredi.
[src:italy/italy-p03] In the 18th century, Italian Rococo was mainly inspired by French Rococo.
[src:italy/italy-p03] Italian Neoclassical sculpture focused, with Antonio Canova's nudes, on the idealist aspect of the movement.
[src:italy/italy-p03] In the 19th century, Romantic painters included Francesco Hayez and Francesco Podesti.
[src:italy/italy-p03] Impressionism was brought from France to Italy by the *Macchiaioli*, and realism by Gioacchino Toma and Giuseppe Pellizza da Volpedo.
[src:italy/italy-p03] In the 20th century, with futurism, Italy rose again as a seminal country for evolution in painting and sculpture.
[src:italy/italy-p03] Futurism was succeeded by the metaphysical paintings of Giorgio de Chirico, who exerted an influence on the surrealists.
[src:italy/italy-p03] Formal Latin literature began in 240 BC, when the first stage play was performed in Rome.
[src:italy/italy-p03] Latin literature was, and is, highly influential, with numerous writers, poets, philosophers, and historians, such as Pliny the Elder, Pliny the Younger, Virgil, Horace, Propertius, Ovid, and Livy.
[src:italy/italy-p03] The Romans were famous for their oral tradition, poetry, drama, and epigrams.
[src:italy/italy-p03] In the early 13th century, Francis of Assisi was the first Italian poet, with his religious song *Canticle of the Sun*.
[src:italy/italy-p03] At the court of Emperor Frederick II in Sicily, in the 13th century, lyrics modelled on Provençal forms and themes were written in a refined version of the local vernacular.
[src:italy/italy-p03] One of these poets was Giacomo da Lentini, inventor of the sonnet form; the most famous early sonneteer was Petrarch.
[src:italy/italy-p03] Guido Guinizelli is the founder of the *Dolce Stil Novo*, a school that added a philosophical dimension to love poetry.
[src:italy/italy-p03] This new understanding of love, expressed in a smooth style, influenced the Florentine poet Dante Alighieri, who established the basis of modern Italian.
[src:italy/italy-p03] Dante's work, *Divine Comedy*, is among the finest in literature.
[src:italy/italy-p03] Petrarch and Giovanni Boccaccio sought and imitated the works of antiquity and cultivated their own artistic personalities.
[src:italy/italy-p03] Petrarch achieved fame through his collection of poems, *Il Canzoniere*.
[src:italy/italy-p03] Equally influential was Boccaccio's *The Decameron*, a very popular collection of short stories.
[src:italy/italy-p03] Renaissance authors' works include Niccolò Machiavelli's *The Prince*, an essay on political science in which the "effectual truth" is taken to be more important than any abstract ideal.
[src:italy/italy-p03] Giovanni Francesco Straparola and Giambattista Basile, who wrote *The Facetious Nights of Straparola* (1550–55) and the *Pentamerone* (1634), respectively, printed some of the first known versions of fairy tales in Europe.
[src:italy/italy-p03] The Baroque period produced the clear scientific prose of Galileo.
[src:italy/italy-p03] In the 17th century, the Arcadians began a movement to restore simplicity and classical restraint to poetry.
[src:italy/italy-p03] Italian writers embraced Romanticism in the 19th century; it coincided with ideas of the Risorgimento, the movement that brought Italian unification.
[src:italy/italy-p03] Unification was heralded by the poets Vittorio Alfieri, Ugo Foscolo, and Giacomo Leopardi.
[src:italy/italy-p03] Works by Alessandro Manzoni, the leading Italian Romantic, are a symbol of Italian unification for their patriotic message and because of his efforts in the development of modern, unified Italian.
[src:italy/italy-p03] In the late 19th century, a literary movement called *verismo*, which extolled realism, played a major role in Italian literature.
[src:italy/italy-p03] Emilio Salgari, a writer of action-adventure swashbucklers and a pioneer of science fiction, published his *Sandokan* series.
[src:italy/italy-p03] In 1883, Carlo Collodi published *The Adventures of Pinocchio*, which became the most celebrated children's classic by an Italian author and one of the world's most translated non-religious books.
